<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Eyes Foreign Investments  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT KEITH-REID
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Buoyed by the lifting of official warnings for
international visitors to stay away, Fiji's new government Thursday
announced incentives aimed at attracting foreign investment to help
repair economic damage caused by a May coup.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase's government announced economic
policies which include slashing corporate tax rates and other
measures to help businesses hard-hit by the coup and spur new
investment.
</P>
<P>
   The South Pacific island nation was plunged into chaos when
failed businessman George Speight led an armed gang into Parliament
on May 19, taking dozens of lawmakers hostage.
</P>
<P>
   A two-month standoff ended when Speight agreed to release his
hostages in return for the military, which took control of Fiji
after the coup, scrapping the 1997 constitution and installing a
new government stacked with nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Ousted Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry is seeking international
support for a campaign to declare Qarase's military-installed
government illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Chaudhry was the first member of Fiji's ethnic Indian minority
to lead the country and his appointment following 1999 elections
crystallized opposition among indigenous Fijians to the growing
economic and political power of Indians, who make up 44 percent of
Fiji's 814,000 population.
</P>
<P>
   The sugar export- and tourism-dependent economy has been
devastated by the crisis -- the sugar harvest was frozen for weeks,
tourist numbers plummeted following civil unrest which targeted
several resorts, and Fiji's most important trading partners imposed
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Australia this week downgraded travel
advisories, noting that the security situation in Fiji has improved
since Qarase's government was appointed. Having earlier warned
their residents to stay out of Fiji, the two nations said visitors
should now maintain a high level of security awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Other incentives announced in the Cabinet document released
Thursday included investment allowances and accelerated
depreciation allowances for businesses, lower duties on
construction materials and capital items, and tax exemptions for
income from export sales.
</P>
<P>
   Full details of the concessions would be announced later, after
consultations with local business organizations, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reserve Bank of Fiji predicted in its latest quarterly
review that economic growth would slump by 13 percent because of
the coup and could deteriorate further into ''the deepest
contraction since records were kept.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the coup, the bank predicted Fiji's economy would grow by
at least 4 percent in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0009 </TRAILER>
