<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police arrest man thought to be involved in a string of violent robberies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A man arrested for attempting to burglarize an
Upper West Side home has been linked to a string of violent
robberies in the same neighborhood, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Van Baskerville, 32, was arrested just after midnight
Tuesday, while attempting to break into a ground floor home on West
95th Street, Detective Joseph Pentangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Baskerville, who appears to be homeless, closely matched witness
descriptions in seven other burglaries on the Upper West Side,
Pentangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   At least three of the robberies turned violent. Earlier this
month, a woman returned to her apartment on West 81st Street and
found her 57-year-old husband on the floor with a fractured skull.
</P>
<P>
   Last month an elderly couple was severely beaten when they
confronted a robber inside their town house on West 87th Street.
Just four days earlier, another elderly couple was beaten and
stabbed in their home on West 93rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Baskerville has past arrests for burglary and criminal trespass,
Pentangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged Wednesday night on a sole count of attempted
burglary, but will be questioned further and placed in a lineup for
witnesses, Pentangelo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
