<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore's Daughter Speaks at DNC  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Al Gore's eldest daughter showed Americans a
human side of him Wednesday -- a dad never too busy with politics to
play with his children.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not asking you to support Al Gore because he is my father,
or even because he's been a great dad,'' Karenna Gore Schiff told
the Democratic National Convention. ''What really matters is what
he will do for all our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Dad is a man of faith in the most gutsy, practical sense. He
wants to see goodness prevail,'' an animated Schiff said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Gore walked on stage, to the delight of the crowd,
and gave his daughter a bear hug. They walked off arm-in-arm as the
crowd roared, and mom Tipper applauded from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Working on the theory that one reason her father -- the vice
president and Democratic presidential aspirant -- is lagging in the
polls is because Americans don't know the real man, Schiff's goal
was to humanize a candidate best known as a stiff policy wonk.
</P>
<P>
   So Schiff, 27 and herself mother of a 13-month-old, highlighted
the role family plays in Gore's life and shared stories of the kind
of father he has been to his four children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's own parents -- Albert Gore Sr. and Pauline -- taught their
son ''about the dignity working people have,'' Schiff said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, his father's family were small farmers; his mother
worked her way through college, becoming one of the first women to
graduate from Vanderbilt Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ''My grandparents taught my dad that it is right to treat every
woman and man with equal respect; to call them Sir or Ma'am; to do
your own physical labor and clean up your own mess,'' Schiff said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, those lessons still resonate, she said. ''He believes in
taking the hard road when that's the road that will take us to
higher ground. And I think his old-fashioned politeness is
refreshing in today's world.''
</P>
<P>
   She offered glimpses of Gore as everyday dad, getting a laugh
when she revealed what he made his kids for breakfast every day --
toast. With lots of butter.
</P>
<P>
   After a big snowfall, the Gores taught their children how to
build an igloo, she said -- as delegates from Alaska cheered.
Karenna and a friend wanted to spend the night in it. Gore bundled
up the kids, ferried hot chocolate out to the igloo and ''welcomed
us like adventurers back from the North Pole'' when ''we ended up
waddling back inside, our lips blue from the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff is one of her father's top political advisers and his
ambassador to the young Generation X voters who she calls crucial
to the November election. So she couldn't resist adding some of
Gore's policy stands to the personal profile.
</P>
<P>
   He's for affordable health care, equal pay for equal work,
fighting big polluters, she said. On abortion, ''I believe in every
woman's right to choose, and I know my father will always, always
defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope, for the sake of our country and our future, that my
father is elected president. But I want you to know to me, he's
already won. For he has been the most wonderful father in the whole
world,'' she concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0020 </TRAILER>
