<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Tries To Calm Liberals  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Introducing himself to America, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman is struggling to stretch across the political spectrum to
mobilize support for Al Gore. Before he gets too far, though, he
has to work on fellow Democrats first.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after being picked as Gore's running mate, Lieberman is
still trying to reassure blacks, teachers, unions and others that
his centrist views are compatible with theirs. Blacks question his
commitment to affirmative action, for example, while teachers are
unhappy about Lieberman's support for school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   It's crucial for Lieberman and Gore to consolidate the base of
Democratic voters because it is not unified now. Behind in the
polls, the Democrats have to turn out their core constituencies at
very high levels to beat Republicans George W. Bush and Dick
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lieberman has to assure some of the people on the far left
that he's not too conservative and go to the middle where the votes
are,'' said American University political scientist James Thurber.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lieberman has to indicate that he's going to be a positive
part of the team in the Gore administration and we're not going to
have to be attacking him,'' says Rep. John Conyers of Michigan,
senior Democrat on the House Judiciary Committee. He said
Lieberman's selection makes it harder to get blacks to go to the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night Lieberman took a star turn at the Democratic
National Convention, accepting the Democratic vice presidential
nomination and hoping to excite voters about his role on the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   He reached wide with an appeal aimed at every shade of Democrat.
He said he marched with civil rights leader Martin Luther King in
the 1960s, registered black voters in the South and believed that
when it comes to affirmative action his philosophy is, ''mend it,
but please don't end it.'' He promised better schools and health
care to every child in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing most Americans know about Lieberman is he is the
first Jew to run on a major party presidential ticket. The second
most trumpeted description is that he was the first Senate Democrat
to scold President Clinton for his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation for moral rectitude makes Lieberman a foil for
Republican promises to restore decency and integrity to the White
House. But Lieberman has caused some anxiety by his frequent
references to religion and values. Some Democrats wish he'd tone it
down.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy broke a religion barrier when he became the
first Roman Catholic elected president. Lieberman hopes to follow
as the first of his faith.
</P>
<P>
   In polls, eight out of 10 people say the country is ready for a
Jewish vice president and nine out of 10 say they personally could
vote for a Jewish candidate. However, pollsters caution that bias
is hard to find since people tend to give socially acceptable
answers.
</P>
<P>
   Like the candidate himself, convention speakers are trying to
broaden the picture of Lieberman's life and ease anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on opening night recalled that Lieberman in
the 1970s had been ''a freedom rider, going into danger to register
black voters in the then-segregated South.'' That was intended to
perk the ears of liberals and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's next remarks reached for moderates and independents.
''It's no surprise Al Gore picked the leader of the New Democrats
to be his vice president,'' the president said. ''Joe Lieberman has
supported all our efforts to reform welfare, reduce crime, protect
the environment and grow the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   A night later, Jesse Jackson said that in selecting Lieberman,
Gore had ''brought the sons and daughters of slaves and
slavemasters, together with the sons and daughters of Holocaust
survivors.'' Sen. Edward M. Kennedy invoked the memory of his slain
brother and said JFK would be proud that Democrats were breaking
''the new barrier of bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny of Lieberman's background and positions is the same
ordeal that Cheney went through when Bush picked him. It's a kind
of political hazing that all running mates encounter. Bush's father
squirmed in 1980 when he was grilled about calling Ronald Reagan's
program ''voodoo economics.'' Cheney took heat for his conservative
voting record.
</P>
<P>
   After a few days in the headlights, vice presidential candidates
tend to fade into the woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know what Woodrow Wilson said about the vice presidency?''
said Boston University presidential historian Robert Dallek.
''There's nothing to say about the vice presidency. And after
you've said that, there's nothing more to say.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's Al Gore who's got to convince the base of the party to
get out there and work for him, to vote and be committed,'' Dallek
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0020 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Uses Humor To Win Voters  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Did you hear the one about Joe Lieberman's
kosher Latino restaurant?
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before about 200 Hispanics Wednesday, Lieberman
quickly won the crowd over with a story about how he and California
Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante, a friend, one night mused that they could
combine their respective ethnic cuisines and open a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we passed the time, we started to think up dishes,'' the
vice presidential candidate said to howling laughter. ''One was
matzoh menudo, and one other I remember is gefilte fish ceviche.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Contreras, 46, a secretary from Union City, Calif.,
practically doubled over laughing. ''He's so funny. I feel like I
know him. I'd seen him before, but I never met him. I was very
impressed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he goes, whenever he campaigns, Lieberman -- known as
the sober centrist who chastised President Clinton for
''embarrassing'' the country -- tries to connect with people in much
the same way a lot of other famous Jewish Americans have, with
humor.
</P>
<P>
   And while he's no Jackie Mason or Jerry Seinfeld, Lieberman
loves to expose his funny bone. He often makes a face, opening his
mouth wide with a smile that says this is the punch line.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood with awe before thousands of Democrats to accept his
party's nomination for vice president, he thanked his wife for her
support and then deadpanned, ''There's an old saying that behind
every successful man, there is a surprised mother-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   He later chided Republicans over their convention last week,
essentially saying they were trying to imitate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may be near Hollywood, but not since Tom Hanks won an
Oscar, has there been that much acting in Philadelphia,'' said
Lieberman. Hanks won the 1993 Oscar for best actor for his role in
the movie ''Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, talking to a group of more than 100 gays and
lesbians at a caucus meeting Wednesday, he had mimicked his
parents: ''When I went into politics, my parents said, 'You can a
making a living from this?''' The accent was pure East Coast
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   When he welcomed running mate Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, to
Los Angeles, before a crowd at the Burbank Airport, he played off a
famous line from Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been waiting for a week to say this and I can't control
myself anymore. In this election, will you help me win this one for
the Tipper?''
</P>
<P>
   And when he and Gore met with hometown supporters from
Connecticut and Tennessee at the Warner Brothers Studios, he
reminded the crowd that the television show, ''The West Wing'' --
the fictionalized White House drama -- is filmed there.
</P>
<P>
   ''Did you know that?'' he asked, warming them up for the punch
line. ''If you and I work hard, the closest George Bush will get to
the west wing is the remote control!'' Lieberman said, again to
laughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0021 </TRAILER>
