<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cards' Williams Told Knee Is Fine  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- Arizona defensive back Aeneas Williams
got the news he wanted to hear when he went to Colorado for a
second opinion on his sore left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The trip home, though, was like something out of the movie
''Planes, Trains and Automobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-time Pro Bowl cornerback traveled to Vail, Colo., on
Tuesday for an examination by noted knee specialist Dr. Richard
Steadman. As was the case in the initial exam by Cardinals team
doctor Russell Chick, nothing serious was detected.
</P>
<P>
   ''The doctor sent me down here and told me to go help lead the
team to Tampa,'' Williams said after practice Wednesday. ''I said
'God bless you, sir, for those kind words.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was when Williams left Steadman's office that things got
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ''My doctor appointment took longer and I missed all the flights
out of Vail,'' Williams said. ''So I stopped at a gas station to
see if I could get on a Greyhound to get to Denver. I had to return
my car to the airport, hitchhike a ride from the airport to the gas
station, and caught a Greyhound to Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   His scheduled 10:27 p.m. flight from Denver to Phoenix was
canceled. But he was able to get on an 8:30 flight that had been
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ''So it's been a lot of fun,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   He said it didn't take him long to catch a ride while
hitchhiking.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the guys recognized me,'' Williams said.
''Unfortunately, he was from Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Steadman agreed with Chick's diagnosis that Williams' injury was
only a bruised knee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything checked out fine,'' Williams said. ''It went real
well. It wasn't anything I ever thought was serious. I just wanted
to get a second opinion. Dr. Steadman assured me I'll be ready to
try to take this team to the Super Bowl in Tampa.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was a full-scale participant in Wednesday's practice,
but coach Vince Tobin said he might hold him out of Friday night's
preseason game at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's fine. If we didn't play it would be only as a
precautionary measure,'' Tobin said. ''They say one thing that
heals it the quickest is rest, and we very well could rest him this
week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0029 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State pauses to watch favorite son accept nomination  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR LOCKS, Conn. (AP) - In bars and gathering places across
Connecticut Wednesday, people watched Joe Lieberman accept the
Democratic nomination for vice president with everything from
raucous enthusiasm for a native son to apathetic indifference.
</P>
<P>
   At Tycoons Restaurant in New Haven, near Lieberman's home, local
Democrats cheered as if a University of Connecticut championship
game was on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a vintage Joe Lieberman speech - thoughtful, humane and
persuasive, with moments of quick wit that only those of us who
know Joe so well are familiar with,'' said state Sen. Martin
Looney, D-New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons doubled over Lieberman's jokes, and gave him a standing
ovation each time he made a point.
</P>
<P>
   In Bob Oliver's opinion, ''it was one of the greatest speeches
I've ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he got his message across in a strong and yet humorous
manner,'' said the New Haven attorney.
</P>
<P>
   But about 40 miles east, at G. Willikers bar in Groton, the
crowd was less enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody asked me to turn it on and nobody is watching it now,''
said bartender Debbie Dousis. ''Talking about politics in a bar can
get pretty heated, so we usually don't talk about politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was similar at the VFW Post 9452 in Preston.
</P>
<P>
   I'm more interested in the Yankees game,'' said Jason Benoit of
Norwich. ''As long as the country is run right, it doesn't matter
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Windsor Locks, businessmen took in the speech at the Cloud
Nine Lounge inside the Shereton Hotel at Bradley Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very excited about it,'' said George Tomljanovic of
Bristol, who settled into the bar for a drink after returning from
a business trip. ''Joe is a very strong candidate coming from a
political background in the past. Religion doesn't play a role in
my perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   But Manuel Riguero, from Miami, didn't think Lieberman would be
a big factor in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think anybody cares,'' Riguero said. ''The vice
president is a dead issue. Vice presidents don't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And although he admires Lieberman's character and commitment to
his religion, Randy Aman of Atlanta, said he fears what will become
of the senator's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he is going to be polluted by the Clinton/Gore
influence,'' Aman said. ''The poor guy is going to get sucked into
the trash.''
</P>
<P>
   In Milford, Democrat Peter Hastings was more encouraged as he
watched the speech at Archie Moore's restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like the fact that he talks about people,'' the engineer
said. ''It seems to me that a lot of politicians forget that
government is the people. He talked about his parents and his wife,
real roots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 0029 </TRAILER>
