<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-TCU Football Player Flowers Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMARILLO, Texas (AP) -- Clyde Eugene Flowers, a two-way tackle
and two-time All-Southwest Conference selection at Texas Christian
in the 1940s, died Tuesday. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, who lived in Houston since 1950, played for TCU from
1940 to 1944 and was elected captain of the team his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of his teammates went to fight in World War II,
Flowers was exempted from the draft for health reasons and stayed
behind. The Horned Frogs were left with mostly inexperienced
recruits and finished 2-6 in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, the Horned Frogs had Flowers, two other seniors -- one
of whom had never played football -- and eight freshmen. Flowers
served as a player-coach that season and the team won the Southwest
Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers was selected All-Southwest Conference in 1943 and 1944.
He played in the 1943 East-West Shrine Game in San Francisco and in
the 1944 College All-Star game in Chicago. Flowers was inducted
into the TCU Hall of Fame in 1977 and into the Panhandle Sports
Hall of Fame in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   He was a longtime employee of American Coatings, a Houston paint
business.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Betty, two sons and a daughter,
seven grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Services will be at 10 a.m. Thursday at Woodlawn Funeral Home
Chapel in Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0039 </TRAILER>
