<HEADLINE> Brewers 5, Reds 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Jeff D'Amico earned his seventh straight
victory and Richie Sexson homered for the second straight game as
the Milwaukee Brewers completed their first sweep of the Cincinnati
Reds with a 5-1 victory Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sexson, playing in his 16th game since being acquired from
Cleveland, hit the first pitch from Rob Bell (5-7) for his fifth
homer following a two-out single by Geoff Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   That was all D'Amico (9-4) needed in boosting his record to 7-0
with a 1.15 ERA in his last nine starts. He scattered eight hits
and two walks in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico allowed a run in the fifth on Dante Bichette's two-out
double over the head of center-fielder Marquis Grissom.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers had a chance to add to their lead in the fifth after
D'Amico led off the inning with his second major league hit, a
double over the head of Ken Griffey Jr. in center field.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico was safe at third as Ron Belliard reached on a sacrifice
bunt that also was a fielder's choice. Two outs later, Scott
Sullivan walked Sexson before getting Jeromy Burnitz on a called
third strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers made it 3-1 in the sixth. Charlie Hayes singled and
with one out Luis Lopez was hit by a pitch. Both advanced on an
error by Sullivan on a pickoff throw before an attempted suicide
squeeze by D'Amico went awry as Hayes was tagged out at the plate
by catcher Jason LaRue. Belliard's bloop single scored Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams squandered several scoring chances and the Reds
stranded two runners in each of the second through fourth innings
before leaving the bases loaded in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers added two insurance runs in the eighth on an RBI
single by pinch-hitter James Mouton and a sacrifice fly by Grissom.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Reds 6&AMP;frac12; games behind St. Louis in the NL
Central. The Cardinals beat Chicago 5-1 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Reds captain Barry Larkin played his 1,800th game. ...
Sexson has driven in at least one run in seven straight games,
matching his career high. ... Bell notched his second hit of the
season, a solid single in the third inning. ... Cincinnati OF
Dmitri Young left the game in the fifth inning after suffering a
bruised right shoulder when he tripped over Sexson at first base on
a ground out in the fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
