<DOCNO> APW20000817.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Tells U.S. To Elect Gore  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Embarking on a ''miraculous journey,'' vice
presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman urged Americans Wednesday
night to elect Al Gore to the White House, hailing him before the
Democratic National Convention as a man of ''vision and values''
who would extend the nation's current prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spoke minutes before delegates formalized Gore's
nomination in a roll call of the states that cemented the
Democratic ticket for the fall campaign against Republicans George
W. Bush and Richard Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president had a cameo appearance on the third night of
his convention. He strode onto the podium to hug his Karenna after
she placed his name in nomination with a speech studded with
reminiscences of her childhood. He did not speak, saving his
remarks for Thursday night's finale.
</P>
<P>
   That left centerstage to Lieberman, the first Jew to take a
place on a major party ticket and little known nationally until
Gore unexpectedly selected him as running mate a week ago. He was
greeted by Democratic delegates waving a sea of red signs
emblazoned with his name. ''Go Joe go,'' delegates chanted. ''We're
gonna go, right to the White House,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman allowed himself a moment of wonder at his fate,
asking, or perhaps declaring, ''Is America a great country or
what?!''
</P>
<P>
   The convention session capped a day in which Gore arrived in
California and proclaimed: ''We're the new guard and we're going to
bring positive change.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the outward displays of enthusiasm, there were
expressions of concern from some Democrats about polls which showed
Bush with a lead of 10 points or so.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of anxiety hanging over this convention,'' said
Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, whose aides have spoken openly about
a campaign in 2004 if the GOP wins the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates heard three nominating speeches for the vice
president. Karenna Gore Schiff, a rising political figure in the
Gore campaign, drew cheers when she said her father would ''always,
always'' defend a woman's right to an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the convention hall, a large, late afternoon crowd of
protesters gathered, standing face-to-face with scores of riot-clad
police. Authorities said arrests for the first three days of the
convention totalled 200.
</P>
<P>
   A few delegates arriving for the convention's evening session
were escorted through the crowd by authorities. Others were
directed to other gates away from the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Little known outside his home state of Connecticut before his
selection by Gore just a week ago, Lieberman touched on his faith,
his belief in Gore and his disdain for Republican policy proposals.
He took pains to offer words of reassurance to blacks who had
questioned his commitment to affirmative action, as well as party
supporters who fretted over his support for school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   He said the time had come to ''tear down the remaining walls of
discrimination in this nation ... and that's why I say, when it
comes to affirmative action, mend it but please don't end it.'' On
education, he said the ticket was ''committed to making America's
public schools the best in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman sprinkled his speech with references to his religion.
He said his ''miraculous journey begins here and now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, introduced him to the delegates,
then met him halfway across the podium. They kissed, twice, then
stepped forward together to acknowledge the cheers. Strains of
Chariots of Fire filled the hall.
</P>
<P>
   His evaluation of Gore as a man of ''vision and values'' seemed
aimed at voters who need reassurance after President Clinton's
well-chronicled personal failures.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said the Republicans ''are decent and likeable men,''
but told delegates to the convention and a nationwide television
audience there are ''very real differences between us in this
election'' and that if elected they would ''squander'' the current
economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   On education, the environment, health care and campaign finance,
he said, the two parties see America ''through different sets of
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   On the economy, he said, Republicans would spend the surplus to
''give a tax break to those who need it least, at the expense of
all our other needs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Under their plan, the middle class gets a little, and the
wealthy get a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm glad the GOP has changed their rhetoric,'' he said, ''but
I wish they would also change their policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign fired right back, with spokesman Ari Fleischer
saying, ''In the ten days Joe Lieberman has been at Al Gore's side,
he has walked away from his position on Social Security, school
choice, and affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's arrival in the convention city marked a new phase of the
campaign. With President Clinton returned to Washington, the vice
president sought to establish his own identity.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts said bluntly that Clinton must
cede the spotlight to allow his longtime understudy to establish
himself. ''We may need to get the Jaws of Life to pry him free from
the thing, but we've got to pry him free,'' Kerry said of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   At an arrival event for Gore, Lieberman added to Gore's
enthusiasm, playfully urging the crowd to ''help me win this one
for the Tipper,'' a reference to Gore's wife, and a play on Ronald
Reagan's old -- and winning -- refrain about winning one for the
Gipper.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of Wednesday's program was Lieberman's speech
followed by the ritual roll call of the states that would formally
deliver Gore's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's wife Hadassah had the pleasure of introducing her
husband to the convention. ''For Joe, family, faith, neighborhood,
congregation and community are the guideposts of his life,'' she
said in prepared remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Security around the city was tight, so much so that some
delegates expressed misgivings. ''Everywhere you go, there's
nothing but police,'' said West Virginia delegate Mary Pearl
Compton.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard his plan en route to California, the vice president
worked on the acceptance speech he will deliver Thursday night.
''He's looking forward to it,'' said Carter Eskew, a top
strategist. ''This is his main chance to be the main guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In arrival remarks, Gore did not mention the man he hopes to
succeed in the White House. ''The future begins here in
California,'' he said. ''The victory begins here in California.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his Thursday night acceptance speech would draw specific
contrasts with the Republicans, and said he intends to fight for a
higher minimum wage, HMO reform, a prescription drug benefit for
Medicare, safety locks for guns and other causes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I need your help to fight for you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides set three nominating speeches to present the vice
president's name for nomination, including one by his daughter,
Karenna Gore Schiff, a rising political figure in the Gore
campaign, and actor Tommy Lee Jones, Gore's roommate during college
at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   A parade of party supporters and elected officials provided
warm-up oratory for the main speech Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, in line to become Speaker if
Democrats win control of the House this fall, pledged that his
party ''will be humble about our beliefs and listen to the beliefs
of others'' if it wins control.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will work with the Republicans to try to find consensus and
bring all Americans along together. Hear me: we will replace 'my
way or the highway' with 'our way together.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman warmed up for his convention address with a series of
appearances before groups of delegates. He drew applause from gays
and lesbians when he declared his opposition to the Clinton
administration's policy of ''don't ask, don't tell'' for the
military.
</P>
<P>
   He told one group he didn't want anyone's vote because of his
religion, but because ''we are the best ticket for America's
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans dispatched a team to rebut the Democratic convention
message. ''We're not here to rain on anybody's parade, we're just
providing some balance,'' said Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash. Still,
she jabbed at Gore and the Democrats. ''We were much better on the
unity front. We solidified our base before we can to the
convention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to the tempests that have swirled at the
Democratic convention, including a controversy over Rep. Loretta
Sanchez and a fund-raiser she originally scheduled for the Playboy
Mansion; as well as questions among Democratic core constituencies
about Lieberman's positions on several issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore high command continued to wrestle with minor problems,
including Nevadans unhappy with the platform position on the
disposal of nuclear waste. The vice president issued a letter to
Sen. Harry Reid of Nevada pledging to veto any legislation that
made Nevada a repository for thousands of tons of nuclear waste.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0102 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Marks Anniversary of Quake  </HEADLINE>
By LOUIS MEIXLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLCUK, Turkey (AP) -- Hundreds of Turks held candles, waved
black flags or simply wept in silence Thursday as Turkey marked the
first anniversary of a devastating earthquake that left at least
17,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   People gathered in central squares in hard-hit towns at 3:02
a.m. to mark the moment that the quake devastated parts of western
Turkey, collapsing more than 285,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are here to remember,'' said Kemal Ozcan, a retired shop
owner.
</P>
<P>
   Ozcan was in his bedroom when the quake struck last year,
collapsing his ceiling and trapping him and his wife beneath the
rubble. They spent almost four hours under the concrete before
neighbors dug them out.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still can't escape the feelings of that night,'' Ozcan
said. ''We can't believe we are alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozcan was lucky.
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away at the memorial service in Golcuk, one of the
hardest hit towns, stood Metin Sagdic. Sagdic survived the quake
with his wife and children, but at least 30 of his relatives were
crushed to death.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel as if it happened yesterday,'' he said. He added that
some of the bodies of his cousins have not been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the earthquake, evidence of the devastation is
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Shattered homes and factories still line the streets of Golcuk,
70 miles west of Istanbul, as well as other towns. Some 26,000
people still live in tent cities, while another 150,000 live in
prefabricated homes that are oppressively hot in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The government has promised to build more permanent housing and
has said most of the tent cities will be closed before winter. But
many people in the quake area are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing has changed,'' said Sagdic. ''We see the same
collapsed buildings one year later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
