Fiji Eyes Foreign Investments
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Buoyed by the lifting of official warnings for
international visitors to stay away, Fiji's new government Thursday announced
incentives aimed at attracting foreign investment to help repair economic damage
caused by a May coup. Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase's government announced
economic policies which include slashing corporate tax rates and other measures
to help businesses hard-hit by the coup and spur new investment. The South
Pacific island nation was plunged into chaos when failed businessman George
Speight led an armed gang into Parliament on May 19, taking dozens of lawmakers
hostage.
