<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Economy Recovering From Quake  </HEADLINE>
By LOUIS MEIXLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADAPAZARI, Turkey (AP) -- Idris Goren spent the past year working
for free on most Saturdays, clearing rubble and repairing machinery
damaged in an earthquake that almost destroyed the train factory
where he works.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts, and those of the 880 other employees who
volunteered with him, have helped the lathes of the state-owned
factory to spin again -- though often in buildings without roofs or
with walls containing holes the size of car tires.
</P>
<P>
   Like the train factory, Turkey's economy is recovering from an
Aug. 17 earthquake that shattered the nation's industrial
heartland, leaving more than 17,000 people dead and flattening more
than 100,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake galvanized the often squabbling members of
Turkey's governing coalition, who quickly banded together and
passed far-reaching economic reforms. The fiscal measures cleared
the way for international loans, increased investment and improved
economic health.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial production, which fell to 30 percent of capacity
after the quake, is back to the pre-quake level of about 75
percent. As a result of disciplined government spending, inflation
fell from a pre-quake annual rate of 65 percent to 59 percent this
June. Inflation should fall to 35 percent by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The damage that was caused by the quake forced (government
members) to get their act together,'' said Atilla Yesilada, an
economist at Bender Securities. ''It unified the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund and the World Bank extended $7
billion in loans to Turkey after it agreed to reforms that included
a multibillion dollar privatization program. The loans helped
Turkey rebuild from an earthquake that caused an estimated $2
billion to $4 billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Aid from the Turkish government went to repair factories such as
TUVASAS, where Goren works to supply the national railroads. While
big plants are mostly back, economists caution that few Turks have
homeowners insurance and almost 175,000 people are still in tents
or temporary houses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many smaller businesses that form a huge part of
the Turkish economy have yet to recover and do not even figure in
official statistics. Turkey's black market economy is at least
three-fourths as large as the official $200 billion economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The big companies are doing well but most of the small and
medium businesses along with their workers were wiped out,''
Yesilada said.
</P>
<P>
   In Adapazari, a major industrial town 90 miles east of Istanbul,
signs of destruction remain everywhere. Abandoned houses that were
torn off of their foundations stand lopsided along roads.
</P>
<P>
   At the TUVASAS factory, crushed train cars lie overturned in a
corner. Twisted train tracks line the floors, swerving in some
places and pinched together in others.
</P>
<P>
   The quake caused $63 million in damage at the factory and killed
three workers who were in their homes when the pre-dawn temblor
struck. A fourth worker was killed during the cleanup efforts when
a block fell on him.
</P>
<P>
   Goren, a mechanic, says he was in shock when he first saw the
mostly destroyed factory. ''We didn't know if it could be
repaired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The workers union rallied the employees, many of whom feared the
factory wouldn't reopen if they didn't pitch in. Nearly
three-quarters of 1,200 workers donated time to the plant, the
largest employer in Adapazari.
</P>
<P>
   The factory now is capable of fixing about 40 train cars a
month, down from the 60 to 65 cars it could fix before the quake.
The train car production line, however, will remain closed for at
least the remainder of the year as repairs continue.
</P>
<P>
   Goren was realistic explaining why he gave so freely of his
time. ''We earn money for our bread from this factory,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
