<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle Boat Struggles To Be Saved  </HEADLINE>
By MIA PENTA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- In its heyday, the Kalakala ferry was considered
a technological marvel. Passengers in the 1930s delighted in its
electric lights, its telegraph machine and its slick art deco
looks.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, the craft was sold to an Alaskan company,
which put it on the mudflats of Kodiak, processed fish in its belly
and let oceans of raindrops beat mercilessly against its hull.
</P>
<P>
   The 276-foot boat was eventually rescued by Peter Bevis, a local
sculptor, who stumbled upon it in 1988 while working in Kodiak as a
commercial fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds greeted the Kalakala's return to Seattle in 1998, and
Bevis imagined a new life for the 65-year-old ferry as a museum,
restaurant or dance club.
</P>
<P>
   Now the up-and-down career of the Kalakala has once again
encountered rough waters.
</P>
<P>
   What was once the pride of Seattle now rusts away on Lake Union,
and the man who poured his heart, soul and pocketbook into saving
her can barely afford basic expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel it's my duty to continue to fix up this boat, to make
sure this project gets finished,'' said Bevis, who borrowed money
and mortgaged his house to rescue the Kalakala.
</P>
<P>
   Initial interest -- and donations -- to fix up the craft have
dried up. The Kalakala Foundation, formed by Bevis and nearly 2,900
volunteers to restore the boat, makes just enough to pay insurance
and moorage.
</P>
<P>
   Bevis still owes nearly $1 million for preparing the Kalakala
and towing it home, and the foundation estimates it needs another
$20 million to restore the boat.
</P>
<P>
   While the public hasn't been generous, many are still
sentimental about the Kalakala. Mayor Paul Schell helped welcome
the boat, and Gov. Gary Locke named last October ''Kalakala
Awareness Month.'' An elementary school teacher was inspired to
write a children's book about the ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should be considered a historic site,'' said 73-year-old
Mary Ellen Kanyer who rode the Kalakala as a child. ''We're not
like the East Coast. We're too young to appreciate antiques.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalakala's financial predicament is not uncommon. Old ships,
especially those left to deteriorate, are expensive to restore,
said Kevin Foster, chief of the National Maritime Heritage Program
of the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Historic ships have little federal or state support. The
Kalakala Foundation did receive a $285,000 federal grant to be
administered by the city of Seattle, but needs $190,000 in matching
funds before it gets any money.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kalakala is a ''one-of-a-kind artifact,''
soliciting money for a boat in its condition is difficult, said Bob
Sittig, executive director of the Seattle-based Maritime Heritage
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen it before, and that's what Peter is up against,''
Sittig said. ''People will never donate to an attraction that looks
like it will never get done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kalakala was launched in 1935 to carry passengers and cars
across Puget Sound. With its streamlined shape and modern electric
conveniences, it embodied the most advanced technology of its time.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was such a radical design,'' said Robert Engstrom, a
retired Washington State Ferries captain who once piloted the
Kalakala. ''It was certainly a showpiece for the Pacific
Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Engstrom, however, believes the Kalakala is best remembered with
fond memories and old pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hate to be a wet blanket, but I think a scrap pile is the
best place for it,'' said Engstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Kalakala Foundation: http://www.kalakala.org
</P>
<P>
   National Maritime Initiative: http://www.cr.nps.gov/maritime
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0117 </TRAILER>
