<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protesters Denounce Cop Brutality  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTINE HANLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Police clashed with bottle-throwing
protesters Wednesday outside the Democratic National Convention
after 2,500 demonstrators marched to the site denouncing police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   An altercation broke out as officers tried to get a truck
through an intersection the protesters had blocked. The protesters
began throwing bottles and other objects at the police, who then
charged with batons. Several rubber bullets were fired.
</P>
<P>
   A few delegates arriving for the convention's evening speakers
were escorted through the crowd. Others walked around to other
gates through the security fence surrounding the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whose streets? Our streets!'' the crowd chanted.
</P>
<P>
   After a standoff, many of the protesters moved north, where
there was another brief scuffle before the marchers returned to a
downtown park near the Staples Centers that they have used as a
base.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the protests broke up, police cited four people for
jaywalking as they returned to the demonstrators' headquarters at
Pershing Square.
</P>
<P>
   During one march, a California Highway Patrol officer was struck
in the chest by a bottle filled with an unidentified liquid that
splashed on his face. He was examined at a hospital and released.
</P>
<P>
   A TV sound technician working for CNN was struck by a police
baton while covering a scuffle. She was treated at a hospital for
rib injuries, a CNN spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have been marching for various causes here since last
weekend, mostly peacefully, watched by hundreds of law enforcement
officers. In fact, during Wednesday evening's standoff speakers on
the official protest stage nearby continued, denouncing the federal
case against Wen Ho Lee, the Asian-born Los Alamos scientist.
</P>
<P>
   The convention city arrest total was near 200 through Wednesday,
but significant violence was limited to a clash after a rock
concert at the protest site Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's demonstration, started as a march to police
headquarters, then proceeded to the convention site. On the way,
helmeted officers carrying batons stood two-deep as activists
shouting in bullhorns and holding banners in Spanish and English
moved across downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates said some demonstrators tried to grab their
credentials as they walked near the convention hall. Police warned
people to hide their tags beneath clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ''They ripped people's credentials off their necks, I think with
the idea of getting into the convention,'' said Matthew Cohen, a
guest of the Connecticut delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service said it had no reports of stolen credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, officers arrested about 30 activists staging
a sit-in at a police station west of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ''No justice, no peace, no racist police,'' protesters shouted
there.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters wearing white gags sat in front of the station's
entrance, going limp as they were arrested and charged with
blocking a public building. They were carried into the station.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at that earlier rally urged the crowd to stay peaceful.
One activist wore a Darth Vader suit, wandering through the
protesters with a baton and making threats of mock arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Among those attending was state Sen. Tom Hayden, a member of the
Chicago 7, the group accused of conspiring to disrupt the 1968
Democratic convention in Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 0143 </TRAILER>
