<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frustrated unions threaten to abandon talks  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Union negotiators for striking phone workers
are threatening to abandon contract talks with Verizon
Communications, frustrated at their sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
   The International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers and some
bargainers for the Communications Workers of America said they
would walk out at midnight Thursday, unless they reach an agreement
or can report substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave an uncertain future for a strike affecting 25
million consumers and now entering its 12th day.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel the progress is slow,'' said Myles Calvey, negotiator
for the IBEW, representing 14,700 employees in New England and
upstate New York. ''It's unfair to us to still be here. It's unfair
to the membership to be out there, quite frankly, with the promise
of an early settlement. We're not going to continue to spin our
wheels while ... members are out on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   IBEW representatives announced Wednesday their intentions to
leave the talks aimed at replacing contracts for nearly 87,000
employees that expired Aug. 6, unless an agreement was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   CWA, which has two sets of negotiators bargaining here, said at
least one of those two tables also plans to leave the talks at
midnight. That table represents workers from New England and New
York as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very possible'' that the other table, bargaining on
behalf of workers from New Jersey to Virginia, could set the same
ultimatum, said CWA spokesman Jeff Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Together, both CWA tables represent more than 72,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon spokesman Eric Rabe suggested Wednesday night that the
threatened walkout could give all parties greater incentive to wrap
up the protracted negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody needs to get down to business to get this thing
done. If this is the way to get people focused on a deadline, maybe
this isn't such a bad thing,'' Rabe said. ''We're perfectly
prepared to do it before midnight tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Gordon, president of retail markets for Verizon, said
earlier Wednesday that he considered an agreement near for part of
Verizon's unionized work force at some of the call centers. Rabe
would not say which workers Gordon referred to.
</P>
<P>
   But Calvey said progress seemed elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can measure it in centimeters, compared to the overall
issues that are out there,'' he said. ''We seem to go forward one
step and back two steps.''
</P>
<P>
   IBEW spokesman Jim Spellane said even issues that reportedly
have been worked out, such as making it easier for the unions to
organize the company's wireless workers, still have details that
need to be hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   The unions also asserted that one of their key concerns - the
movement of work from Bell Atlantic territory to GTE's region -
remains unresolved. The two companies together formed Verizon in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The CWA says workers fear that Verizon executives will be
rewarded as the company expands nationally, while rank-and-file
employees will be forced to move or take lower-paying jobs to stay
at their current locations.
</P>
<P>
   The strike affects directory assistance, service and repairs in
Delaware, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, New
Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Virginia,
West Virginia and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com
</P>
<P>
   Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 0155 </TRAILER>
