<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 17; Nasdaq Adds 15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed Thursday, as fears of a
second-half profit slowdown continued to plague the markets.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 16.85 at 10,991.54.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.80 to 1,484.65, and the
Nasdaq composite index was up 14.51 at 3,875.71.
</P>
<P>
   The latest earnings scare arrived Thursday when analysts
forecasted a slowdown in computer giant Hewlett-Packard's
second-half profits.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard shares fell $10.562 to $109.438.
</P>
<P>
   A selloff in retail stocks dragged down the Dow index on
Wednesday as investors fretted that second-half profits could fall
short of expectations if consumer spending eases in step with the
Federal Reserve Board's policy of cooling the economy to fight
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Now those fears have apparently crept into the tech sector.
</P>
<P>
   Economic data released recently has signaled that the Fed's
strategy to slow the economy may be working.
</P>
<P>
   However, while a slowing economy may prevent the Fed from
raising interest rates, it also raises the specter of lower
second-half profits.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts consider the Fed's policy of cooling the economy
through higher interest rates a double-edged sword and are hoping
for what's referred to as a soft landing, meaning economic growth
eases but not so much that it hurts companies' bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Labor Department's Consumer Price Index, a
widely watched barometer for inflation, showed that consumer prices
rose a mild 0.2 percent last month, as the cost of gasoline eased
after soaring in June.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that the economy is cooling, the Commerce
Department reported Wednesday that housing construction fell 3.3
percent in July to the lowest level in at least two years. It was
the third straight monthly decline.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues narrowly outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 127.52 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 0.37 to 512.37.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.19 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.84 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.28 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
