<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 38; Nasdaq Adds 54  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were higher Thursday, as investors
sought out industries likely to escape an expected slowdown in
second-half corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 38.46 at 11,046.85.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 13.09 to 1,492.94, and
the Nasdaq composite index was up 54.23 at 3,915.43.
</P>
<P>
   ''This market has been fairly lifeless recently. But if there's
been one theme -- and it's been hard to find one -- it's that
investors are concerned for earnings in the second half,'' said
Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've just gotten through the second-quarter earnings period
and the numbers were very strong. But the picture is not going to
be as pretty in the third and fourth quarters. So investors are
trying to find those industries and companies that won't be
affected by the slowdown in the growth of earnings,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson cited semiconductors, communications equipment, drug
companies, electric utilities and the oil sector as areas investors
believe may emerge relatively unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, shares of telecommunications parts maker Ciena
Corp. rose $10.50 to $173.75 on Thursday after the company
forecasted better-than-expected fourth-quarter earnings based on
projected demand for fiber-optic parts.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement gave an across-the-board boost to Internet and
telecom equipment companies.
</P>
<P>
   The latest earnings scare came from Hewlett-Packard, however.
Two analysts expressed concern for the computer giant's second-half
profits, sending shares of the number two U.S. computer maker down
$11.50 to $108.50.
</P>
<P>
   A selloff in retail stocks dragged down the Dow index on
Wednesday as investors fretted that second-half profits could fall
short of expectations if consumer spending eases in step with the
Federal Reserve Board's policy of cooling the economy to fight
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economic data released recently has signaled that the Fed's
strategy to slow the economy may be working.
</P>
<P>
   However, while a slowing economy may prevent the Fed from
raising interest rates, it also raises the specter of lower
second-half profits.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts consider the Fed's policy of cooling the economy
through higher interest rates a double-edged sword and are hoping
for what's referred to as a soft landing, meaning economic growth
eases but not so much that it hurts companies' bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''The good news is that the Fed probably won't raise interest
rates,'' Johnson observed. ''But the bad news is that the rate of
earnings will slow and that's what investors are focusing on.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues narrowly outnumbered decliners on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 405.34 million shares, down
from Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 0.60 to 513.34.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
