<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Montenegro, Milosevic Parties Meet  </HEADLINE>
By ALEN MLATISUMA
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Putting aside bitter rivalries,
members of Montenegro's pro-Western government and opposition
parties loyal to President Slobodan Milosevic met Thursday to
discuss ways to avert conflict ahead of Yugoslav elections.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was the first in a year bringing together
high-ranking party officials from the ruling pro-Western Democratic
Party of Socialists and their bitter opponents and Milosevic
loyalists, the Socialist People's Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both sides agreed that it is absolutely necessary to preserve
peace as the primary condition for stability and the future of
Montenegro,'' the small republic's prime minister, Filip Vujanovic,
said after the three-hour talks.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions escalated in Montenegro after Milosevic scheduled Sept.
24 parliamentary and presidential elections. Yugoslavia is made up
of the dominant Serbia, Milosevic's power base, and Montenegro, a
republic of only 600,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The independence-minded Montenegrin leadership is calling for a
boycott of the elections on grounds that the ballot cannot be fair
after Milosevic changed the country's constitution and set new
election rules in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional changes also considerably weakened
Montenegro's clout in the two-house federal parliament. To take
part in the elections would, according to Montenegro's reformist
leadership, amount to ''giving legitimacy to efforts by the
Belgrade dictatorship to prolong its political survival.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The differences on the elections issue in Montenegro must not
be a cause for armed conflict,'' Vujanovic also said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were told the talks would continue, but no date was
given.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's (meeting) is the start of a dialogue that can be
successful only if the two parties seek sincere solutions in the
interest of Montenegro, its citizens and the union with Serbia,''
Predrag Bulatovic, a Milosevic ally, said earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition in Serbia says the Montenegrin boycott call plays
into Milosevic's hands, making it easier for pro-Milosevic parties
to take control of the 50 seats Montenegro holds in the Yugoslav
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's regime has accused the Montenegrin leadership of
working to break up Yugoslavia, and says the elections will be a
unique referendum on whether the country is to remain ''free'' or
be turned into a colony of the United States and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences with Serbia, Montenegro's leaders have
hesitated to proclaim full independence.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic, the chief Milosevic foe,
fears armed clashes between the bitterly divided blocks in
Montenegro should independence be formally declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 1249 </TRAILER>
