<HEADLINE> Philippine Hostage Release Delayed  </HEADLINE>
By PAT ROQUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- Government negotiators scrambled
Thursday to put the release of Western hostages held by Muslim
rebels back on track after President Joseph Estrada rejected a plan
that would have left three French journalists still in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather Thursday also prevented the negotiators from flying
to Jolo, a remote southern island where Abu Sayyaf rebels are
holding the captives in jungle hide-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado, who until
Thursday was willing to settle for an initial release of the nine
Western tourists, said Estrada insisted that the three TV
journalists be released at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ''He reminded me of his instruction that the negotiating panel
should work for the release of everybody,'' Aventajado said. As a
result of the shift, ''we need an extra day to do all the
preparations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are expected to release all 28 hostages, including
the tourists and the journalists, between Friday and Monday, said
Aventajado, who was to meet Friday with ambassadors from the
foreign hostages' countries.
</P>
<P>
   The hostages include three French, three Malaysians, two
Germans, two Finns, two South Africans and one Filipino still in
captivity from the original group of 21 people abducted April 23
from Malaysia's Sipadan diving resort. The rebels later seized the
three French journalists and a dozen Filipino Christian evangelists
who visited the rebels' hide-out to pray for the Sipadan hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's meeting with the ambassadors was called after the
rebels apparently made new demands for the release of the
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Other last-minute negotiations involve security arrangements for
the hostages' turnover, officials said. Negotiators want to ensure
that the hostages and government officials are not attacked by
armed groups on the island, while the rebels fear they may be
targeted by the military.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the rebels released Lucrecia Dablo, a Filipino
cook who worked at Sipadan. She was the first hostage to be freed
since the release of six Malaysians and one German last month.
</P>
<P>
   About $5.5 million was paid for those releases, according to
military estimates. The large ransoms have led to fears of an
increase in future kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   Libya has played a high-profile role in the negotiations for the
Western hostages and is believed to be paying millions of dollars
for their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Former Libyan Ambassador Abdul Rajab Azzarouq, a member of the
Philippine negotiating panel, has denied reports that Libya is
paying as much as $25 million to the rebels and says his country
will fund development projects in the southern Philippines instead.
</P>
<P>
   Libya hopes its prominent role in freeing the hostages will
enhance its international image. It plans to fly the Western
hostages to Tripoli to meet with Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi
before they return to their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   Libyans have been pleased with their government's efforts to
release the hostages, saying they prove their country is not a
terrorist state as some Western countries charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a good step by my country and an act that makes me
more honorable,'' said el-Hadi Mohammed, a 53-year-old taxi driver.
''Western media always say that Libya is a terrorist state and this
proves the opposite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 1302 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
