<HEADLINE> Hulk Hogan Files Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Hulk Hogan has filed a defamation suit against
the World Championship Wrestling, accusing the WCW's creative
director of berating him on national television after a ring
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Hogan won the July 9 bout in Daytona
Beach, Fla., by default when his opponent refused to wrestle, but
the WCW's Vince Russo followed Hogan from the ring, accused him of
''playing politics'' and implied he is dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   WCW spokesman Alan Sharp declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some have speculated that the lawsuit might be a publicity
stunt, as part of a continuing story line in which the WCW has
sought to eliminate older wrestlers such as Hogan as it tries to
revive flagging ratings. Hogan has not appeared on WCW programs
since the lawsuit was filed Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a real lawsuit,'' said Hogan's attorney, John Taylor
Jr. What Russo said ''was defamatory and a breach of contract.''
</P>
