<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Mum on Pentagon Sub Offer  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russian government officials have not
responded to Defense Secretary William Cohen's offer to provide
U.S. military assistance to the stricken Russian submarine, the
Pentagon said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter delivered to Russian officials Tuesday, Cohen
expressed concern for the fate of the 118 crew members aboard the
Kursk, which sank to the bottom of the frigid Barents Sea on
Saturday. ''My department stands ready to provide any assistance
you need; please do not hesitate to ask,'' Cohen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A Cohen spokesman, Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, said Cohen received
no response, although the crew of a U.S. deep-water rescue vessel
based near San Diego is prepared to go to the scene if the Russians
ask for it.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton discussed the matter with President Vladimir
Putin in a telephone call Wednesday and offered U.S. assistance.
That same day the Russian military requested help from Britain,
which has a mini-submarine en route to the scene, and Norway, which
is preparing to send a team of divers.
</P>
<P>
   Quigley said it remained possible that the United States could
provide help if the Russians asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's never too late,'' Quigley said. ''If the Russians feel
that there is something that the United States or any other nation,
for that matter, could provide to assist in the rescue of the crew
members, we're very confident that they will say so. And we'll do
our very best to provide that, whatever that might be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spokesman also said the United States has ''heard
no form of communication'' from the crippled Russian submarine
since it went down, although he later said, ''We have no direct
knowledge as to whether or not there's been tapping or any other
form of communication with the crew members of the submarine.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. surface ship with sophisticated listening devices was
positioned a couple hundred miles from the scene of the accident at
the time, Quigley said, but he would not say what, if anything, it
has heard.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Thursday that U.S. sensors in the area detected two explosions from
the stricken submarine at the time of the accident. Officials
earlier this week said one explosion had been heard. It remains
unclear what caused the explosions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
