<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New law requires inspection and licensing of pet dealers  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A new law will require pet stores and
breeders in New York to be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   The law signed by Gov. George Pataki requires ''pet dealers'' to
maintain records on the origins and medical history of dogs and
cats and provide the information to buyers. Dealers also must
comply with statewide minimum standards of animal care, such as
providing appropriate housing, food and veterinary care.
</P>
<P>
   Pet stores and breeders will have apply for licenses, renewable
annually, from the state Department of Agriculture and Markets.
</P>
<P>
   The department will also inspect facilities at least once a
year. Violations may lead to fines from $50 to $1,000, or
suspension or revocation of licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say the new law targets ''backyard breeders,'' some of
whom currently don't keep records or aren't providing adequate
care.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just paying a fee, getting a form and a license to
operate. You need to meet those thresholds in order to operate,''
said Lisa Weisberg, vice president of government affairs at the
American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (ASPCA).
</P>
<P>
   ''There should be no reason why consumers who purchase a pet
from a local shop should have to question the health of the animals
they buy,'' said Assemblyman Scott Stringer, a Manhattan Democrat
and bill sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The law applies only to the care of cats and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, pet dealers have to bring animals to a licensed
veterinarian within five business days of sale for a complete
checkup. Animals 18 months old or older will also have to be
checked for congenital diseases, and dealers will have to inform
customers of any such problems in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Proper vaccination and other health records are also required.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the state's ''pet lemon law'' went into effect,
requiring pet dealers to guarantee the good health of any animal
they sell. Customers who purchase sick animals have 14 days to seek
refunds or exchanges. The law also requires the stores to reimburse
owners for medical bills up to the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Another ''implied warranty and merchantability'' law has also
been applied to pets and entitles pet owners to reimbursement
within two years of purchase, Weisberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of the pet dealer licensing law will ensure that
animals, as well as consumers, are protected, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 1624 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge dismisses charges filed against concrete attack suspect  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan judge on Thursday threw out an
attempted murder charge against a man who confessed to bashing a
young woman's head with a five-pound chunk of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal Court Judge Donna Recant dismissed the charge at the
request of Assistant District Attorney Amy Schwartz, who said an
investigation by her office revealed that Bentley Louis Grant, 35,
is not the assailant.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's investigation uncovered a surveillance
videotape showing Grant in a Virgin Records store on July 9 at the
time Tiffany Goldberg, 25, of Madison, Wis., was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who was apparently homeless at the time, was picked up
July 19 and charged in the attack. Goldberg, who had just left
Marble Collegiate Church on Park Avenue at 29th Street where she
sings in the choir, suffered a cracked skull, broken teeth, a black
eye and cuts and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz balked at a request by Grant's lawyer, Natasha
Lapiner-Giresi, for the videotape. The prosecutor said Grant is not
entitled to the tape because no charges are pending against him,
and the case is over.
</P>
<P>
   Lapiner-Giresi did not say why she wanted the tape, but Grant's
civil attorney, Patrick Joyce, said he plans to file a lawsuit
against the city on Grant's behalf within the next 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce, who could try to bolster the civil case with the tape,
said he believes the police settled on Grant as a suspect and
stopped looking for anyone else. He said the assailant evidently
''is still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapiner-Giresi said outside court that the charges should have
been dropped on July 24 when Schwartz came to court and said
evidence showed police had arrested the wrong man.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the apparent mistake, Grant is not bitter,
Lapiner-Giresi said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we walked out of the courtroom he said to me, 'I hope that
woman goes on with her singing career, and I hope she does well,'''
the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she didn't know why Grant confessed or why three
witnesses identified him as the assailant.
</P>
<P>
   He now has a place to live and is doing ''fine,'' Lapiner-Giresi
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not going to the hospital. He has an apartment, and he
intends to continue living his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 1625 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
