<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Builders join chorus of protest over DEP's sewer proposal  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Department of Environmental
Protection's proposal for new regulations on sewers and water
quality isn't making anyone happy.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Builders Association, which represents most of
the state's housing developers, has denounced the DEP's proposed
sewer rules as too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference with developers Wednesday, association officials
issued a position paper claiming regulations that link the impact
of new housing to area water quality will limit builders in areas
where there is plenty of sewer capacity to build new homes,
according to spokeswoman Roberta Wells.
</P>
<P>
   The association paper said this change in rules will reduce the
construction of affordable homes in the next two decades when tens
of thousands of families will be seeking them. ''It will inflate
costs statewide, reducing the housing and employment opportunities
of middle and modest income families,'' the association's paper
said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, environmental groups have been attacking the DEP's
proposed rules as too weak in limiting sprawl by exempting some
sewerage authorities from seeking new permits to expand their
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   DEP spokesman Peter Page said, ''There has been the most
hyperbolic rhetoric from the environmentalists, and now from the
builders.''
</P>
<P>
   Page said all the state is trying to do is make sure new
development does not damage area water quality. That is not only a
question of sewage treatment but also of how surface runoff from
new streets, roofs and driveways influences a ''watershed,'' which
is the region feeding rain runoff into a lake or stream.
</P>
<P>
   Page acknowledged the change in strategy embedded in these rules
is substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rule is a major shift in how we are going to oversee land
use in New Jersey because we are making the direct connection
between water quality and development,'' Page said. ''Simple
reality now is that when you put development into an area that is
undeveloped, you degrade water quality.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have every confidence that developers are going to be able
to build with creativity and technology that is going to be
friendlier to the hydrological cycle,'' Page said, referring to the
life cycle of how waterways and groundwater systems flow and are
recharged.
</P>
<P>
   But the builders association in its position paper said the DEP
is avoiding the full picture. ''Regulating future development is
only one piece of a true water quality strategy. Given New Jersey's
historic development patterns, significant progress in improving
the state's water quality is possible only by addressing existing
causes of pollution, including outdated technologies'' in sewer
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Page said all the complaints about the proposed rules will be
taken into account. They will be reviewed starting Oct. 9 and
subject to change, at which point they will be published publicly
again before taking effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 1650 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business news in brief from around New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) - Lucent Technologies said Thursday that
it has received a contract worth up to $200 million from Sprint
Corp. to expand the telecommunications carrier's Internet network.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will help Sprint keep pace with its soaring demand
for Internet access and enhanced Internet services such as virtual
private networks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Lucent will supply its APX 8000
Multiservice Access Switch, NavisAccess network management software
and NetworkCare professional services, which includes program
management, installation and testing. Sprint will use Lucent's
Softswitch Internet Call Diversion solution to route data traffic
away from its voice network to prevent congestion and provide
customers with faster and easier access to the Internet, Lucent
said.
</P>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The Prudential Insurance Co. of America said
Thursday that it has agreed to acquire a majority stake in one of
Taiwan's largest asset-management companies for about $95 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential said it would obtain at least 80 percent of
MasterLink Securities Investment Trust Enterprise's outstanding
stock, under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1992, MasterLink has nearly $1.6 billion in assets.
It offers 13 mutual funds, including eight domestic equity, three
overseas equity and two domestic bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''MasterLink fits into Prudential's preferred profile for
international asset management acquisitions. This company has a
large, retail-oriented customer base in Taiwan and a high
percentage of regular monthly savings accounts that bring strength
and stability to the company's assets under management,'' said
Douglas Fergusson, president of Prudential Asia.
</P>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON, N.J. (AP) - Continental Choice Care Inc. announced
Thursday that it has changed its name to TechSys Inc. It will begin
trading on the Nasdaq small cap market as early as next week under
its new symbol, TKSS.
</P>
<P>
   The new name reflects the former dialysis company's new focus on
investing in and acquiring information technology businesses.
TechSys said it will focus on business in emerging markets such as
India.
</P>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Department of Community Affairs
announced Thursday that it is providing more than $200,000 in
grants for job training for urban women.
</P>
<P>
   The funding is being channeled through the state's Job Training
Center for Urban Women. The program provides grants to nonprofit
agencies and educational institutions for the implementation of job
training programs and other services to assist unemployed and
underemployed urban women.
</P>
<P>
   The program awarded $110,000 to the Camden County Council on
Economic Opportunity, $85,000 to the New Jersey State
Federation/Colored Women Clubs Inc. in Trenton and $35,000 to Essex
County College.
</P>
<P>
   EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) - The Regional Consortium, a group of
five transportation agencies committed to bringing E-ZPass to
Northeastern highways, said Thursday that more than 500,000 E-ZPass
tags have been issued since the electronic toll system was
introduced on the Atlantic City Expressway and Interstate 95 in
Delaware in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that we have issued over one-half million
transponders in just 20 months of operation proves that the
motorists appreciate and value the hassle-free, more convenient
commute provided by E-ZPass,'' said Edward Gross, executive
director of the New Jersey Turnpike Authority, the lead agency of
the consortium.
</P>
<P>
   E-ZPass should be installed at interchanges along the turnpike
on Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden State Parkway first opened E-ZPass lanes on the
Parkway last December. Each toll plaza along the 173-mile stretch
will be equipped with E-ZPass by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   The Parkway's New Gretna toll plaza opened its first E-ZPass
lane Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
