<HEADLINE> Bill and Chelsea Clinton register to vote in NY  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - As Al Gore nudged his boss away from
the political center stage, President Clinton moved a step closer
to his post-White House life, changing his voter registration from
Arkansas to Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   The county Board of Elections added Clinton and daughter
Chelsea, 20, to the voter rolls Wednesday, a week after receiving
their registration forms, Commissioner of Elections Reginald
Lafayette said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president looks forward to exercising his right to vote in
the great state of New York,'' White House spokesman Jake Siewert
said. ''He thinks he'll have some good candidates on the ballot
this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Westchester residents will next go to the voting booths for the
state's Sept. 12 primary, when a little-known New York City
orthopedic surgeon, Mark McMahon, challenges Hillary Rodham Clinton
for the Democratic Senate nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, who is expected to face Republican Rep. Rick
Lazio in the general election, registered to vote in Westchester
County in December, shortly after the Clintons bought a $1.7
million wood-frame house in Chappaqua.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Chelsea Clinton listed the Chappaqua home as their new
address, according to Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pleased to have him as a voter,'' the elections
commissioner said. ''I'm sure that he's going to volunteer to work
at the polls. ... I think he'll help me out after Jan. 20.''
</P>
<P>
   The president signed his registration form on Aug. 4 and Chelsea
signed hers on Aug. 1. The Board of Elections received the forms
Aug. 9, Lafayette said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's good for the county of Westchester to have the
president live here,'' Lafayette said.
</P>
</TEXT>
