<DOCNO> APW20000817.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicklaus Puts Mother's Death Aside  </HEADLINE>
By TIM DAHLBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- For once, Jack Nicklaus didn't want to be
on a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   For once, it looked like he didn't belong.
</P>
<P>
   With the death of his mother weighing heavily on his slumped
shoulders and Tiger Woods playing brilliantly beside him, Nicklaus
seemed a weary figure Thursday as he trudged around steamy Valhalla
Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that he shot a 5-over 77 and likely won't make
the weekend cut in his final PGA Championship, an event he
dominated in his prime.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt sort of inadequate out there today,'' Nicklaus said.
</P>
<P>
   A day after his mother died at the age of 90, Nicklaus honored
one of her last wishes by playing in the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Nicklaus had feared her death would interfere with her
son's plans to play all four major championships for the last time
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no desire to be here, I promise you,'' Nicklaus said.
''But I felt that this is what she would have wanted me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus was paired for the first time with Woods, in a symbolic
changing of the guard featuring the player many consider the best
golfer ever and the one most consider will become the greatest
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remember, bears eat tigers,'' Nicklaus' wife, Barbara
whispered in his ear as he went to the first tee.
</P>
<P>
   Not at the age of 60, they don't. And not when the Tiger next to
him was shooting an effortless 66.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a day when Nicklaus was going to kid himself about
his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ''He plays a game which I am not familiar with,'' Nicklaus said,
borrowing the line Bobby Jones said when he saw Nicklaus play as a
young man. ''Of course, I played a game today I was not familiar
with, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The large crowd following the featured group, which also
included Masters champion Vijay Singh, barely had a chance to cheer
their favorites off the first tee, and Nicklaus was already 2 over,
thanks to a double bogey from left of the green, on the first hole.
</P>
<P>
   He was 4 over after five holes, before a beautiful up-and-down
from deep weeds beneath the sixth green seemed to help settle him
down. The day suddenly seemed to brighten for Nicklaus, and he
promptly made his only birdie of the day on the next hole.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a hard time getting focused to start with,'' Nicklaus
said. ''I wish I had played better, but I tried as hard as I
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods saw what was going on, and understood.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could tell he wasn't really into the round,'' Woods said.
''But once he got into the rhythm of playing, you can tell his mind
started getting more and more sharp and started concentrating more
on each and every shot. Once he got more into it, he started
playing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus had played with Woods in a practice round before the
Masters a few years ago, but never in competition. He got a chance
to see up close what all the fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   In his prime, it was Nicklaus hitting it past all the
competition. On Thursday, Nicklaus outdrove Woods only when he hit
driver to Woods' 2-iron -- and then only by 10 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to play with Tiger before I retired from the game,''
Nicklaus said. ''I haven't seen anyone else play this well. His 66
was just a piece of cake. It could have easily been a 60.''
</P>
<P>
   The pairing reminded Nicklaus of the time he played with Gene
Sarazen in 1971 at the PGA Championship, when Sarazen's playing
days were basically over.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a real privilege for me to play with him and it was
fun,'' Nicklaus recalled. ''I am sure he had the opportunity to get
to watch me in the prime of my career at the same time. And I am
getting the opportunity to watch Tiger in the prime of his career.
It was something I have wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans lining the fairways of Valhalla shared in that
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching each green, usually with Woods in front, the cheers
rose for each player, with the loudest reserved for the aging
champion of 18 major tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank you, Jack. Thank you,'' one fan shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ''God bless your mama,'' another called out from behind the 18th
green.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Nicklaus seemed almost energized by the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's my last major championship or not, I had a unique
experience and enjoyed it very much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus then prepared for a quick flight to Columbus, Ohio, to
be with family members preparing for his mother's funeral service
on Monday. He planned to be back for one final major championship
round on Friday, playing with Woods and Singh in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The day started tough, but now Nicklaus was actually looking
forward to Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully I can shoot a little better score tomorrow,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 1726 </TRAILER>
