<HEADLINE> New York's rainfall almost twice as much as summer average  </HEADLINE>
n0545nyny-
r n BC-NY--SummerRainout 2ndLd-Writethru   08-17 0523
BC-NY--Summer Rainout, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0502
New York's rainfall almost twice as much as summer average
EDS: CORRECTS to La Nina sted El Nina in 18th graf.
AP Photo
By REAGAN HAYNES
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The unseasonable rain is not likely to let
up, matching areas with the most summer rainfall in the continental
United States, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   If it continues as predicted, New York's summer precipitation
will be akin to Miami, which has some of the wettest summers in the
country. New York's August rainfall so far is about five times the
August average in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, New York has received about 15 inches of rain; the
average is 10 inches. The August average of 4 inches has already
been surpassed and it's expected to keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the forecast Ken and Karen Jones of Huguenot wanted
to hear. The water in their Hudson Valley driveway is a foot deep
and fills the area from the street to their garage door.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say it's at least 50 feet wide,'' said Deerpark Town
Supervisor James Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the nightmare story of the guy who bought some land and
it turns out to be a swamp,'' Ken Jones told the Middletown Times
Herald-Record.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said roads and driveways have been washed out because
there has been too much rain for the water to soak into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has torn out a great big drain on one of our town roads,''
Chandler said, adding that the pipe, about 6 feet in diameter,
ripped out the road.
</P>
<P>
   Massive driveway puddles are common this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been there all summer,'' Margaret Hart said, describing
the puddle as about 6 feet long. ''It's quite a bit of water.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing you can do about it,'' said Christine Kronau,
Hart's mother. ''I was golfing last night and you could see huge
ravines where the water had come down hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Terri Goetz said her tractor sank when she and her husband tried
to tend to their acre and a half in Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pond overflowed, the pool overflowed,'' Goetz said. ''We
had to pump the extra water out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a picnic table at ''On the Farm,'' an outdoor eatery
in a suburb of Albany, Vicki Francese chatted with her co-workers
on a lunch break from Concord Pools.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of angry customers,'' Francese said of the
company that sells and installs pools. ''Only because there is so
much groundwater, we can't get a lot of work done.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Person, who took orders from behind the counter, said the
food stand, usually ''jam-packed'' in the summer, was slow.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who wants to stand in the rain and get ice cream?'' Person
asked.
</P>
<P>
   La Nina, a massive body of cool water in the Pacific, might be
partly responsible for the excessive rain, said Bob Chartuk of the
National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Also affecting the precipitation Chartuk called ''considerably
above average'' is the jet-stream that pushed summer showers
northward, almost doubling precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   Although temperatures rounded out to about average, most of New
York has not seen a high temperature above 85 degrees since June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
