<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cavs' Knight Has Knee Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cleveland Cavaliers point guard Brevin Knight
had right knee surgery Thursday and is expected to be out up to
four months.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's knee has bothered him for about a month and he had a
bone fragment removed from his kneecap.
</P>
<P>
   ''We anticipate a full recovery and look forward to his return
to the Cavs' lineup,'' general manager Jim Paxson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brevin has been a very consistent performer in his first three
years with the Cavs.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight averaged 9.3 points and seven assists in 65 games last
season, including 46 starts.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken by Cleveland out of Stanford with the 16th pick in
the first round of the 1997 NBA draft. He became the team's
starting point guard as a rookie, earning a spot on the league's
All-Rookie team.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of last season, the 5-foot-10 Knight became a
backup to rookie Andre Miller. Knight missed 14 of the 15 games
between Feb. 5 and March 10 with a right quadriceps tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers signed 10-year guard Bimbo Coles to a contract
Saturday. He also can play the point guard spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
