<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senators' Bonk Wins Arbitration  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Ottawa Senators forward Radek Bonk got a big
raise Thursday as NHL arbitration hearings wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   The center was awarded a two-year deal worth $3.25 million. He
will make $1.5 million in 2000-2001, a hefty raise over his salary
last season of $800,000, and $1.75 million the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Bonk had 23 goals and 37 assists in 80 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   In other decisions, Dallas Stars right winger Blake Sloan was
awarded a one-year contract worth $550,000, an increase over last
year's $375,000.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two players filed for arbitration in 2000, and 18 of them
settled with their respective teams before going to a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary Flames goaltender Fred Brathwaite was the biggest
winner, going from a salary of $373,400 to $950,000, an increase of
156 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Capitals defenseman Brendan Witt saw the smallest
gain. He will stay at the same $1 million for 2000-2001 and will
get a $75,000 increase the following year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
