<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UConn's Auriemma Gets $2.95M Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. (AP) -- The University of Connecticut is rewarding
women's basketball coach Geno Auriemma with a new five-year, $2.95
million contract four months after he led the Huskies to their
second national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma, who has coached the team for the past 15 years, will
be paid $590,000 annually, which is $307,000 more than under the
old contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''Geno has personally directed the building of a great college
basketball program which has brought positive national recognition
to our entire university,'' UConn athletic director Lew Perkins
said Thursday in a prepared statement. ''This new agreement
recognizes coach Auriemma as the nation's top women's basketball
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract is retroactive to Aug. 11 and runs through April
14, 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The annual compensation includes a base salary of $164,000 and
another $426,000 for speaking fees and media appearances.
</P>
<P>
   UConn athletic officials say no taxpayer dollars are used to pay
Auriemma. The money comes from Athletic Department revenue sources
such as gate receipts, private fund-raising, corporate
partnerships, television and radio rights fees and money from the
Big East Conference and the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   UConn men's coach Jim Calhoun will make $879,984 this year. He
signed a five-year contract last year after his team won the NCAA
title.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun also has a base salary of $164,000 a year, but his
speaking fees and media appearance money come to $715,749 annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
