<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union files complaint against job agency  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - An agency that helps people find jobs is
being accused of unlawfully firing two employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Federation of Educational and Professional
Employees accused Global Associates of dismissing two employees of
Connecticut Job Corps because they were trying to organize a union.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints with the National Labor Relations Board in
Hartford seek to reinstate the employees with back pay and
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Global Associates, a government contractor based in Irvine,
Calif., denied the allegation but declined to discuss why the
employees were fired.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Belton-White, who was a counselor and taught high school
diploma equivalency classes, said she was discharged two days after
a manager at Connecticut Job Corps asked her about her union
activity.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I began to assist in organizing, I was immediately
dismissed,'' she said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Belton-White said managers told her she was fired for bringing a
Bible to class and for failing to follow counseling procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hodel, who had been a social worker and counselor at the
job center for more than 4 years, said he also was fired after
trying to organize a union.
</P>
<P>
   Hodel said he was told he was dismissed for failing to turn in
the proper paperwork. He is legally blind and uses a wheelchair,
and alleged managers did not give him the assistance he needed or
the correct paperwork to fill out.
</P>
<P>
   Global Associates did not even know the employees were trying to
form a union, said Tina Cato, vice president of program
development.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't discuss why they were terminated, but I can tell you
they were not terminated for union activity,'' Cato said.
</P>
<P>
   The frequent turnover of counselors and teachers is harming the
students who come to the center to get their high school
equivalency diploma or learn a trade, such as culinary arts or
medical assisting, Hodel said.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 students between the ages of 16 and 26 attend classes
at the center for up to 2 years. Older students with handicaps are
allowed to stay longer.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher's union is trying to organize about 100 counselors,
teachers, kitchen workers and security guards at the job center.
The workers want better pay and job security, said union organizer
Greg Kotecki.
</P>
<P>
   The agency operates on a $5 million grant from the U.S.
Department of Labor, said Wayne Smith, a spokesman from the Boston
office.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the U.S. Labor Department is not investigating the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any kind of grievance or complaint they might have is
something they should take up with Global,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Global Associates is a privately held contractor that does work
for the U.S. Department of Defense and U.S. Department of Labor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 1756 </TRAILER>
