<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge hands motion picture industry a landmark victory over DVD piracy </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A federal judge Thursday gave the motion picture
industry considerable legal ammunition to protect DVDs from being
copied on computers.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling that further defines the legal boundaries of the
Internet, U.S. District Judge Lewis A. Kaplan conceded computer
codes were ''a matter of First Amendment concern,'' but he rejected
arguments they should receive maximum constitutional protection and
be exempt from government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Computer code is not purely expressive any more than the
assassination of a political figure is purely a political
statement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came in a case in which eight leading Hollywood movie
studios sued a Web site publisher to stop him from making available
online, or posting links to, software that descrambles the code
meant to prevent DVDs from being copied.
</P>
<P>
   The software, developed last year by a 15-year-old Norwegian
youth, has helped make it possible for computer users to copy
full-length feature films from digital versatile discs onto their
hard drives or other recordable media.
</P>
<P>
   Leon P. Gold, a lawyer for the Motion Picture Association of
America, said the ruling ''establishes once again that you cannot
take anyone's copyrighted work without permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president and chief executive officer of the
Motion Picture Association of America, called Kaplan's 90-page
decision the ''stoutest defense of the sanctity of copyright that
I've ever read.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear. It is eloquent and, most of all, it has
absolutely no ambiguity whatsoever,'' Valenti said. ''I think this
is going to send a clanging alarm bell in the ear of every venture
capitalist.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a loss for Eric Corley, the editor and publisher
the Web site 2600.com and the print publication ''2600: The Hacker
Quarterly.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Garbus, a lawyer for Corley, said Kaplan's findings were
''what we expected'' and said he plans to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We understood that this was an issue that has to be resolved
by the Supreme Court. The judge's First Amendment analysis is
wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Kaplan issued a preliminary injunction forcing
2600.com to remove the DeCSS code from his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, though, the Web site in what has been described as
an act of ''electronic civil disobedience'' has provided links to
nearly 500 other sites offering the DeCSS code.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the Web site obviously meant to frustrate the
effect of any ruling he might make.
</P>
<P>
   Gold said some damage had been done.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the floodgates never opened and I think this decision will
prevent the floodgates from opening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a 90-page ruling Thursday, Kaplan issued a
three-page final judgment finding that the posting of the DeCSS
code violated the Digital Millennium Copyright Act, a 1998 law
aimed at controlling software piracy and the posting of copyrighted
material on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ''We always felt this was exactly the case the statute was
written for,'' Gold said. ''If the court had failed to file an
injunction, we didn't think there would be anything left of the
statute.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.2600.com
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of American: http://www.mpaa.org/
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Copyright Office: http://www.loc.gov/copyright
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Copyright Law: http://www.loc.gov/copyright/title17/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
