<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 47; Nasdaq Gains 80  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose modestly Thursday as oil producers
and brokerages powered the Dow, while semi-conductors and
fiber-optics makers charged the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average lifted 47.25 at 11,055.64.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 79.67 at 3,940.87, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index gained 16.22 to 1,496.07.
</P>
<P>
   Trading remained light as it has been in recent days leading up
to next Tuesday's Federal Reserve meeting. With numerous signs the
U.S. economy is cooling off, investors are betting the central bank
will leave interest rates steady.
</P>
<P>
   ''This market has been fairly lifeless recently. But if there's
been one theme -- and it's been hard to find one -- it's that
investors are concerned for earnings in the second half,'' said
Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've just gotten through the second-quarter earnings period
and the numbers were very strong. But the picture is not going to
be as pretty in the third and fourth quarters. So investors are
trying to find those industries and companies that won't be
affected by the slowdown in the growth of earnings,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson cited semiconductors, communications equipment, drug
companies, electric utilities and the oil sector as areas investors
believe may emerge relatively unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, shares of telecommunications parts maker Ciena
Corp. rose $15.938 to $179.188 on Thursday after the company
forecasted better-than-expected fourth-quarter earnings based on
strong demand for fiber-optic parts.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement gave an across-the-board boost to telecom
equipment companies, including Nokia, which rose $2.313 at $41.438.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a surge from rising oil prices, petroleum producers
enjoyed a broad rally. Exxon rose $1.043 to $83.813 and Chevron
added $1.731 at $87.188.
</P>
<P>
   Intel led a rally among semiconductors, moving up $2 at $70.063.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that J.P. Morgan is in play as a merger target
fueled financial services stocks. J.P. Morgan rose $2.562 at $145
and Lehman Brothers rose $8.625 at $135.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard beat second quarter earnings estimates but
analysts expressed concern for the computer giant's second-half
profits, sending its shares down $12 to $108.
</P>
<P>
   Economic data released recently has signaled that the Federal
Reserve's strategy to slow the economy may be working. However,
while a slowing economy may prevent the Fed from raising interest
rates again this year, it also raises the specter of lower
second-half profits.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts consider the Fed's policy of cooling the economy
through higher interest rates a double-edged sword and are hoping
for a ''soft landing,'' meaning economic growth eases but not so
much that it hurts companies' bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''The good news is that the Fed probably won't raise interest
rates,'' Johnson observed. ''But the bad news is that the rate of
earnings will slow and that's what investors are focusing on.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues beat decliners by a narrow margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where composite volume came to 1.11 billion
shares, down from Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 3.72 to 516.46.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.19 percent,
Germany's DAX index was down 0.50 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 0.21 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.73 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
