<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students file lawsuit against high school's drug testing policy  </HEADLINE>
By HANAH CHO
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Three students filed a lawsuit against a
Hunterdon County high school Thursday, challenging what civil
rights activists say is a random drug testing policy for those who
park on campus or participate in athletics and extracurricular
activities.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union of New Jersey filed the
lawsuit on behalf of the families of three students who attend
Hunterdon Central Regional High School in Flemington.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Salyer, a staff attorney with the ACLU, said the policy
violates student privacy rights under the state constitution and
provides no justifiable reason for testing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Random suspicious-less testing is what it boils down to,''
Salyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The policy was adopted during the last academic year, but goes
into effect Sept. 8, Salyer said. It is an expansion of an existing
1997 policy that randomly tested student athletes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not sure how many students it will cover,'' Salyer said.
''At some point, it will be every student in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has allowed random drug testing for
student athletes if a school shows reasonable suspicion, but state
courts have been broader in interpreting individual privacy rights,
Salyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Salyer said although the New Jersey Supreme Court has never
ruled on a case involving school drug testing policies, a state
Superior Court judge stuck down a drug testing policy at
Carlstadt-East Rutherford Regional School District in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Ridgefield Park school district dropped a drug
testing policy after a lower court issued a temporary injunction
against the school for failing to justify the testing, Salyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Singling these students is not only unfair but
counterintuitive,'' he said. ''It's hard to show a special need
when they are the good kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The three students represented in the lawsuit include a varsity
gymnast, a Model United Nations participant and a writer with the
school's online literary magazine.
</P>
<P>
   High school officials barred Shaun Joye from participating in a
school play last spring when his parents refused to sign a consent
form authorizing the drug test, Salyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Students from Raritan, Readington, Delaware, East Amvell and
Flemington attend Hunterdon Central Regional High School.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Hunterdon Central Superintendent Judith Gray said she
couldn't comment on the lawsuit because she has not received a copy
of it.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone message left for school board president John Brasell
was not immediately returned Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
