<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio pokes fun at Clinton campaign 'tracker'  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OWEGO, N.Y. (AP) - They call him ''the tracker.''
</P>
<P>
   A young man armed with a video camera and tape recorder has been
trailing Rep. Rick Lazio's Senate campaign for weeks now - and on
Thursday the candidate ended a stump speech outside the Tioga
County Courthouse by acknowledging him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me introduce someone else,'' Lazio told a small group of
supporters, explaining that ''tracker'' Eric Schultz is a
Democratic Party worker who has been following the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's all say hello to Hillary Clinton and the whole Clinton
campaign,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Twice before, Lazio has acknowledged Schultz on the campaign
trail. He offered him a slice of pizza a few weeks ago at a
Brooklyn pizzeria and on Tuesday, he gave Schultz his subway pass
after an appearance in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz declined to comment after being singled out by Lazio. He
referred questions to the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''The person we send is respectful, he never disrupts events.
The fact that Rick Lazio is so worried about it makes you wonder
what he's hiding,'' said spokesman Peter Kauffmann of the state
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   While the whole encounter seemed like sophomoric political
hijinks, Lazio said he was disturbed by both Schultz and a man
dressed in an Uncle Sam suit who constantly asks Lazio to release
his tax returns. (The congressman has promised to do so by the end
of the month.)
</P>
<P>
   ''What I am disappointed about is what their intent is,'' Lazio
said. ''Their intent is a malicious ... to go around and to
distract and to undermine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island congressman left no doubt who is to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're coordinated with the Clinton campaign, and she's got
an opportunity to speak out against it. She chooses not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Levine, a spokeswoman for the Clinton campaign, said
tracking is a common practice in political campaigns and Republican
trackers have attended many of Clinton's appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ''The difference is she doesn't complain about it,'' Levine
said. She added, ''When Hillary's at a public event she assumes all
of her comments are public, and the same is true for Rick Lazio's
events.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign is so vexed that staffers sometimes put
placards in front of Schultz's camera and employ other
cat-and-mouse tactics to keep him from photographing Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the entire campaign recognizes Eric's escapades for
what they are, kind of laughable in a sad way,'' said campaign
spokesman Patrick McCarthy. ''Even the congressman recognizes that
and that is why a couple of times he has acknowledged him at
events.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 1823 </TRAILER>
