<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweep Leaves Indians Tired, Reeling  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- It was nearly 2:30 a.m. EDT Thursday by the
time the Oakland Athletics rallied for three runs in the ninth
inning to beat the Cleveland Indians and sweep a crucial three-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   Many Indians fans had gone to bed long before the A's mounted
their comeback from a 5-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland owner Larry Dolan was just sorry he wasn't one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately,'' Dolan said when asked if he had stuck it out
until the bitter end. ''And then I stayed up a little longer
afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians didn't return from their six-game West Coast road
trip until 8:30 a.m., and adding insult to injury, the team's bus
got caught up in morning rush-hour traffic as it approached
downtown Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   These days the wild-card standings are just as congested.
</P>
<P>
   After taking two of three games in Seattle, the Indians were
swept in Oakland, going 2-4 on the important trip. Cleveland is
three games behind the A's in the wild-card race, and the Indians
are behind Boston, too, in the battle for the final playoff spot,
too.
</P>
<P>
   And right behind the Indians are the Anaheim Angels and Toronto
Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Losing to the A's took away any momentum the Indians had built
while away. Now they head into a weekend series against the Seattle
Mariners. Cleveland will get another crack at the A's when Oakland
comes to town for three games next week.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's game, Cleveland manager Charlie Manuel had
assessed the importance of the series finale.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a big game, but it's not the end of the world if we
don't win a game here. Any time there's a two-game swing, it's a
big game.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a big one to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' bullpen wasted a solid start from Chuck Finley, who
tired in the seventh after giving up three runs and seven hits in 6
1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Finley had gone more than six innings only one other time in his
last six starts, so Manuel turned to his relievers to close out the
win.
</P>
<P>
   But first Paul Shuey, then Steve Karsay and finally Bob Wickman
let the A's overcome the four-run deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ''From our standpoint there wasn't a lot of good things,'' said
Travis Fryman, who homered twice and drove in four runs. ''The
offense performed well and Chuck Finley pitched a good game, but
ultimately it wasn't enough. It's disappointing because we had a
chance coming in here to make up ground. That hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Indians were still awaiting word on Jaret Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who is out for the season, underwent arthroscopic
surgery on his right shoulder in Los Angeles on Thursday, and the
club had not heard what Dr. Lewis Yocum had found.
</P>
<P>
   Wright has a frayed labrum in the shoulder and the team was
hopeful that he would be able to rehab in time for the start of
spring training in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 1825 </TRAILER>
