<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts say two untreatable diseases have attacked state's tobacco crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SOUTH WINDSOR, Conn. (AP) - Two untreatable diseases have
attacked the Connecticut Valley's broadleaf tobacco crop,
threatening to destroy a large part of it.
</P>
<P>
   This year has seen the worst cases of the brown-spot and
hollow-stalk diseases to hit the Connecticut River valley in the
last 50 years, farmers and tobacco processors said Thursday. They
blame the summer's cool, wet weather for the outbreak of the two
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a major disaster,'' Sherwood Waldron, general manager of
South Windsor Tobacco Farms, a division of National Cigar Corp.,
told the Journal Inquirer of Manchester. ''A lot of people have had
to get rid of their crops.''
</P>
<P>
   The diseases attacked at a time when the blue mold epidemic that
plagued tobacco crops during the past three years has waned as a
result of effective countermeasures by farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural officials said broadleaf tobacco typically grows
best in hot, humid weather without too much rain.
</P>
<P>
   Brown spot is a fungus that causes rings or spots on leaves
containing dead tissue. The disease, which typically develops from
July through September, grows in the lower leaves and moves up the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Hollow stalk is caused by bacteria that invade the cell walls of
tobacco plants and soften the leaves and stalks. The two diseases
are usually found in mature or overripe tobacco crops.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the biggest outbreak in the last 50 years,'' says James
LaMondia, a plant pathologist at the Windsor-based Connecticut
Agricultural Experimental Station. ''Some crops have been severely
affected. Quite a few acres have had to be torn up.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadleaf tobacco is used as a wrapper in cigars. The leaves
must be free of blemishes to be marketable, LaMondia said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Eddy, executive director of the Farm Service Agency of
Hartford and Tolland counties, said that if the cool, damp weather
continues through September, about half of the roughly 2,400 acres
of broadleaf tobacco grown this year in the Connecticut River
valley will be lost to the two diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 1840 </TRAILER>
