<HEADLINE> Helms Upset About Dalai Lama Snub  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, accused the United Nations of being
''weak-kneed'' for excluding the Dalai Lama from a conference of
religious leaders from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am upset,'' Helms, R-N.C., said in a letter Thursday to
Richard Holbrooke, U.S. ambassador to the world body.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 religious leaders have been invited to the
Millennium World Peace Summit on U.N. property this month, but the
Tibetan Buddhist leader was left out for fear of offending China.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Ambassador, can it be that the United Nations has chosen
to appease the Communist dictators in Beijing -- who drove the Dalai
Lama into exile in the first place and who continue to oppress the
Tibetan people -- rather than include one of the world's most known
and respected spiritual leaders?'' Helms wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Surely you share my dismay that the organizers of a 'world
peace summit' would choose to exclude a Nobel Peace Prize winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama, who was awarded the 1989 Nobel, fled Tibet in
1959 with thousands of supporters after a failed revolt against
Chinese rule of the mountain region.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is not an official sponsor of the summit,
which has received funding from Ted Turner's U.N. Foundation,
Better World Fund and others and was organized by a coalition of
interfaith leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But the first two days of the summit will be held in the U.N.
General Assembly chamber, and a U.N. official advised organizers
that China would be outraged if the Tibetan spiritual leader was
invited.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers asked the Dalai Lama to attend the last two days of
the conference and to give the concluding speech -- all scheduled at
a New York hotel, away from the United Nations. He declined.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering, scheduled for Aug. 28-31, will bring together
leaders of religious groups worldwide to discuss conflicts and
initiate religiously based efforts to resolve them.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Glynn, a spokeswoman for Holbrooke, said he ''is as
upset as Senator Helms is that the Dalai Lama was not invited and
thinks that should be rectified immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   United Nations: http://www.un.org
</P>
<P>
   Dalai Lama: http://www.dalailama.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 1841 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Mitchell Gets His Chance  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Last year, Basil Mitchell had no idea
what he would do if the Green Bay Packers cut him.
</P>
<P>
   This week, injuries have turned Mitchell into Green Bay's
starting running back, giving him no time to think about his sudden
-- albeit temporary -- rise through the NFL's pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries to Dorsey Levens and Ahman Green have put Mitchell on
top of the Packers' depth chart before their preseason game at
Miami. Mitchell, who had just 29 carries last year as Levens'
rookie backup, could get that many just Monday night at Pro Player
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not really a whole lot of pressure on me, because I've
been through this before,'' Mitchell said. ''I had to help out last
year in a lot of different ways. I'm not afraid to fight for a spot
on the team, and now I've got a great chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Sherman said the Packers are unlikely to sign a
veteran running back to tide them through the preseason and the
regular season's first two games, both because of salary cap issues
and the enormous amount of learning a new back would need to do in
a short time.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a difficult thing to do, and besides, we like the
guys we have,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he didn't specifically mention Mitchell, Sherman's plan
amounts to a backhanded vote of confidence for his third-string
runner. Mitchell has proven his worth on special teams, and he has
impressed Packers coaches with his pass-blocking and pass-catching
abilities as a third-down back.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure whether Mitchell is ready to be the featured
runner in the Packers' offense -- except Mitchell, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can do it,'' Mitchell said. ''It's not the best situation
for our team because Dorsey is one of the best backs in the game,
but I can help out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is hoping to make the Packers' roster with a second
straight outstanding training camp. Though he came to Green Bay as
an undrafted free agent from Texas Christian in 1999, he was Green
Bay's leading rusher during the preseason and became one of the
team's top kickoff returners.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a guy who realizes he has to good at a lot of things to
be valuable to this team,'' Packers running backs coach Kippy Brown
said. ''He fills a lot of roles for us, and he makes the most of
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell thinks he did so well in training camp last year
because he had no fallback plan. He knew virtually nothing about
any NFL teams except the Packers and his hometown Dallas Cowboys,
and he had no idea whether anyone but Green Bay was interested in
him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very motivated by that, and I'm still motivated today,''
Mitchell said Thursday. ''I fit into this team very well, and they
know what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mitchell was kicked in the same big toe he had
offseason surgery to fix. The minor, nagging injury kept him out of
three workouts, but on Thursday morning he was back at practice
despite lingering pain.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to come out and get some work,'' he said. ''I just
have to keep it taped up and keep getting treatment on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is needed for depth in practice as well as in games.
Levens had arthroscopic surgery on his left knee on Tuesday, and
Ahman Green sprained his knee Sunday at Denver. Both are
tentatively expected to be back in 3-4 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of training camp, Mitchell faced stiff competition
even for the third-string spot from rookie Rondell Mealey, but the
seventh-round pick blew out his knee in the first preseason game
and had ligament surgery this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of guys are going down, and that's not good, but it
helps me,'' Mitchell said. ''I have mixed feelings about a lot of
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
