<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Twins Will Pitch Case for Outdoors  </HEADLINE>
By ARNIE STAPLETON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Twins will learn Tuesday
whether they have the go-ahead from the Metrodome to play some
games outdoors next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins wanted the Metropolitan Sports Facilities Commission
to meet before then. But the state's open meetings law doesn't
allow it, said Bill Lester, executive director of the commission,
which owns and operates the dome, home to the Twins and Vikings
since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Lester said a meeting to vote yes or no on the proposal was set
for Tuesday at the commission's offices inside the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is designed to drum up public support for a new
outdoor ballpark for the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Twins receive consent from the commission, they face
major barriers in getting their wish to play the Sept. 18-20 series
against Texas at a temporary 25,000-seat ballpark that would be
erected near the Mall of America.
</P>
<P>
   The club also would have to obtain authorization from the
commissioner's office, the players' association, the Rangers and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Twins met with Lester on Thursday to review
concerns that he had outlined in a letter Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In that letter, Lester told Twins general counsel Ben Hirst that
the Twins would have to reimburse the Metrodome for lost revenue
and also would need to address concerns over concession and sign
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission's biggest concern is a fear that the Vikings
would seize the opportunity to break their own lease, which runs
through 2011.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which would like to renovate the Metrodome into
a football-only facility, asked the Twins to get a guarantee in
writing from the Vikings stating that they wouldn't use such a
waiver as precedent to break their lease.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings, who are pushing for a new stadium, refused.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't like the word deal-breaker,'' Lester said of the
Vikings' rebuff. ''But that's a major obstacle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
