<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Break for Mediate at PGA  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE BAILEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Rocco Mediate came into the PGA
Championship sky-high after a victory in last week's Buick Open.
</P>
<P>
   He may leave Valhalla Golf Club flat on his back.
</P>
<P>
   Mediate suffered a freak injury before his 9:04 a.m. tee time
Thursday and could be forced to withdraw from the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before my round, I went to sit on a chair where the caddies
gather on the patio outside the clubhouse and the chair
collapsed,'' Mediate said in a statement. ''I fell and landed on my
right side, injuring my neck, shoulder and lower back.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiff and sore, he played the opening round and struggled to a a
5-over-par 77.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it had not been the PGA Championship, I wouldn't have
played,'' the statement said. ''It bothered me most on iron shots
when I had to bend.''
</P>
<P>
   Mediate was expected to wait until Friday -- he has a 1:15 p.m.
tee time -- to decide whether to withdraw from the year's final
major.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was a sharp turn from the good fortune Mediate had
at the Buick. He never led, then birdied the last hole to tie
leader Chris Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Perry's first bogey in 29 holes gave Mediate his
fourth career victory.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   FAN BASE: Tiger Woods wasn't the only player drawing a raucous
crowd during Thursday's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   John Daly, who was an unlikely winner at the 1991 PGA
Championship, also commanded large galleries as he made his way
around Valhalla with playing partners Wayne Grady and Greg Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd gathered three- and four-deep at the seventh green
cheered loudly when Daly made an 8-foot birdie putt to reach 1
over.
</P>
<P>
   Shouts of ''You da man, John!'' and ''Grip it and rip it!'' were
heard often as he strolled from the greens to the tee boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Dave and Susan Blyford, of Cincinnati, followed Daly rather than
tournament favorite Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ''John's just a regular guy who happens to be able to play
golf,'' Dave Blyford said. ''He's had his problems like most people
do, and he still keeps plugging along. You've got to love that.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly often acknowledged the crowd between holes, thanking them
for their support.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's fun to watch,'' Susan Blyford said. ''Besides, there's no
way we'd even get close to Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly finished Thursday with a 2-over 74.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   1990 AGAIN: Early in his first round, Wayne Grady played the
type of golf he hasn't since winning the 1990 PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Grady rolled in a 25-foot uphill putt to birdie the first hole,
then blasted out of a greenside bunker at the par-5 second hole and
watched the ball roll in for an eagle.
</P>
<P>
   He made the turn at 1 under, and two birdies and two bogeys on
the back side left him with that score entering the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy with the final score,'' said Grady, whose only title
since his major victory came at the 1991 Australian PGA.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got off to a very good start, then it was a bit of a mixed
bag after that. I drove it well but hit a few bad iron shots, so in
the end, 71 was a good score.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   YOU DO WHAT?: Jean Van de Velde wasn't surprised when playing
partner Mark Brown told him he was a club professional.
</P>
<P>
   But he was absolutely stunned to find out that Brown, who
finished Thursday at 1 under, makes his living selling clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked him, 'How often do you play?,' and he said 'Never,' ''
said Van de Velde, who shot a 70. ''That's pretty depressing for
us, isn't it? He doesn't even play every day of the year and he hit
the ball 10 times better than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 34, the head professional at Tam O' Shanter Club in
Brookville, N.Y., said he was thrilled to be playing in his first
PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't sleep (Wednesday) night,'' he said. ''I hit a drive
on No. 1, hit a good wedge shot and made birdie. That kind of got a
load off me and I finally was able to start to play some golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde said Brown should ponder a career change.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is he thinking about? He's got the talent to be out here,
no doubt about it,'' Van de Velde said. ''He strikes the ball so
well and he is very athletic. He's got a good attitude and is very
relaxed. I think he should reconsider what he is going to do in his
next 10 years. If I was him, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   DIVOTS: Dudley Hart, ranked 27th in the world, withdrew from
the tournament following a 79, citing severe back pain ... The
green at the par-3 eighth includes a massive valley on the left
side. John Daly hit an iron shot that looked as if it would stick
within a few feet of the hole, but the ball coasted down the hill.
''Thanks a lot, Jack,'' Daly said, referring to the course's
designer -- Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
</TEXT>
