<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At naval bases, tears, flowers and reminiscences mark memorial  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKEHURST, N.J. (AP) - Some wept quietly, some held single
carnations in memory. They giggled listening to some of the
eulogies. They fought back tears during others.
</P>
<P>
   And when a lone bagpiper began to play ''Amazing Grace,'' more
than 1,700 mourners crammed into the base gymnasium at Lakehurst
Naval Air Engineering Station sat deadly still, united in grief.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of our prayers and remembrances and ceremonies cannot do
the one thing we want most - that is, to bring them back,'' said
Vice Admiral Joseph Dyer, summing up the grim reality of the
memorial service held Thursday for nine of the 11 victims of last
week's midair plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the victims worked at the naval base, but all nine were
well-known to base staffers for their work in Naval aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a stage where framed color photographs of the
victims sat on easels, beneath a giant American flag that hung on
one wall, Naval officials and representatives of each victim's
family took turns reminiscing during the two hour and 45-minute
service Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   David Dahlen, 57, of Warminster, Pa., a retired U.S. Navy
commander who worked in logistics at a Navy facility in
Philadelphia, was remembered by his daughter as a NASCAR buff and
barber shop quartet singer. ''In my Mom's words, my Dad epitomized
the words 'an officer and a gentleman,''' said his daughter,
Debbie.
</P>
<P>
   Angelos ''A.J.'' George, 39, of Toms River, who worked in
foreign sales of military aircraft, was a former Eagle Scout who
considered ''Kool Aid, Pop Tarts, burritos and Busch beer'' the
four basic food groups, said his brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanical engineer Cindy Kovacs, 39, of Robbinsville was
remembered by friend Regina Celin as a dedicated mother, courageous
breast cancer survivor and an ''intelligent, great-looking babe
with killer legs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People have been saying the most wonderful things about you,''
Celin said, addressing Kovacs as if she were present. ''You'd be
embarrassed,'' she said, fighting back tears.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph P. Mari, 37, of Toms River, one of the pilots of the
Piper Navajo, loved to fly and used to tilt his wings to say hello
as he flew over his home, sister Susan Kearney said. ''Joe always
said, 'If I'm going to die, let it be in the air.' Well, Joe, you
got your wish,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The two planes collided over a subdivision about 10 miles south
of Trenton on Aug. 9, sending wreckage hurtling into a Burlington
Township home and setting it ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers implored the mourners to celebrate the lives of
the victims, not their untimely deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thirty-nine years of outstanding life will not be overshadowed
by one tragic day,'' said a man - he did not identify himself -
speaking on behalf of victim Robert G. Polo, 39, of Barnegat.
</P>
<P>
   Dyer and base commander Capt. Stephen Himes called the victims
''teammates of ours'' who died in service of their nation. U.S.
Rep. Chris Smith called them ''vital links in our national
security.''
</P>
<P>
   When the service ended, hundreds of the mourners stayed behind
to lay carnations on the table in front of the victims'
photographs. One widow knelt on both knees, crying and holding her
dead husband's photograph in her hands, kissing it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
