<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Megan's Law notification delivered to state Capitol  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - In the building where Megan's Law was
created and signed, prosecutors went office to office in the state
Capitol Thursday to warn workers that a dangerous sex offender had
moved into the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   They visited staff members of legislators who voted for the
bill. They visited the governor's office, where it became law. And
they visited reporters - warning them not to share the information
with the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Under Megan's Law, community members are notified when convicted
sex offenders deemed to pose a continuing threat move into an area.
Some notifications are limited to schools and day-care centers. But
those involving the highest-risk offenders are given out door to
door to residents and to people who work in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the convict is a 65-year-old disabled man who
lives a few blocks away from the Capitol and has been classified as
a posing a high risk of committing another offense.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, community members notified about offenders must
not share the information with anyone who does not live or work in
the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty for violating that provision is a contempt of court
charge. However, the state Supreme Court ruled recently that the
penalty clause of the law was illegal. That ruling has been
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters based at the Statehouse huddled with their editors
after being informed of the notification meeting. Fliers with
information about the sex offender were given only to those who
signed a form pledging to keep it confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a highly unique and peculiar circumstance,'' said
Mercer County Prosecutor Daniel Giaquinto, who conducted the
notification meetings personally.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Supreme Court ruling, Giaquinto told reporters they
still could face contempt-of-court censure from Superior Court
Judge Andrew Smithson if they reported specific information about
the sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time warning notices were delivered to the
Statehouse and state offices around it.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman, who signed the act into law on Oct. 31,
1994, was in Los Angeles Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The law was named for 7-year-old Megan Kanka, who was raped and
murdered six years ago by a convicted sex offender who was living
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Steven Finkel said if Megan's Law is to
survive court challenges, the sanctity of the information
disseminated about sex offenders is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are at risk of losing the protection of the law,'' Finkel
said. ''We are doing this for your personal safety.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Public Defender's Office said distributing
the information to the media is troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's notification, especially to members of the working
press, does underscore the need for adequate safeguards to be
established to prevent the unauthorized distribution of private
information contained within Megan's Law notices,'' spokesman Jeff
Beach said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 1855 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
