<HEADLINE> More infected birds, mosquitoes prompt further spraying for West Nile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - New evidence of West Nile virus in four of the
city's five boroughs will lead to more pesticide spraying to kill
disease-carrying mosquitoes, city officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Three birds - one in Central Park, one in northern Manhattan and
one in Queens - tested positive for the virus this week. In
addition, 27 mosquito pools infected with West Nile were found in
Staten Island, Manhattan and the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said the city will spray the affected
areas this week, including Central Park on Friday night and again
on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Three elderly Staten Island residents have been infected with
the virus this summer. All are recovering.
</P>
</TEXT>
