<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildwood ride worker loses leg in Haunted House ride mishap  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WILDWOOD, N.J. (AP) - A 19-year-old amusement ride worker lost
his leg after it became entangled in the track of the ride during
operation, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Jackson, a college student from Ireland who was working
here for the summer, had his left leg amputated Wednesday night on
the Monster Mash Haunted House ride, Lt. Steven Long said.
</P>
<P>
   The ride consists of a series of open cars that travel on an
enclosed track through the haunted house, which is a converted
movie theater. Jackson's job was to jump out of the darkness to
scare riders, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somehow, he either tripped or just got entangled in the
track,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was taken by helicopter to Atlantic City Medical Center,
where he was listed in fair condition Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The ride was shut down after the accident and will remain so
pending an investigation by the state Department of Community
Affairs, which regulates amusement rides in New Jersey, according
to department spokesman E.J. Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda did not know when the last time a worker was injured on
an amusement ride in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration also is
investigating the accident.
</P>
</TEXT>
