<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Must-See-Tiger TV  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD FENDRICH
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to golf these days, it seems every producer
figures it's ''Must-See-Tiger TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's the only golfer that's taken golf from the third, fourth,
fifth page of the sports page to the very front page of a lot of
newspapers,'' said Lance Barrow, coordinating producer of CBS
Sports' coverage of the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you ever get too tired of watching Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers might have at last week's Buick Open, when The Golf
Channel showed Woods on tape instead of first-round leaders live.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Sports had vowed to avoid the same type of folly with
Thursday's first-round coverage of the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   When TNT's golf coverage started, at 1 p.m. EDT, viewers saw
Woods and playing partner Jack Nicklaus on tape or live, almost
exclusively, for the first hour.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at about 2:45, viewers saw another package of taped
highlights of Woods. And, just in case anyone had missed it, there
was another recap of Woods' day at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   His round started more than three hours before the CBS-produced
telecast went on the air from Valhalla Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   What was nearly impossible to determine while watching, though,
was that Masters champion Vijay Singh was the third member of
Woods' threesome.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, apparently, didn't merit much coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Scott Dunlap, whose 6-under 66 tied him with Woods for
the clubhouse lead.
</P>
<P>
   All that face-time for Woods means airtime for his sponsors,
which Justin Leonard thinks could eventually help other golfers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Non-golf companies are stepping up and saying, 'You know, we
can get a lot of exposure (by sponsoring Woods).' And they all
can't have Tiger,'' Leonard, the 1997 British Open champion, said
on ESPN's ''Outside the Lines'' last weekend. ''They all want him.
But they all can't have him or afford him. And when that doesn't
happen, then maybe some of that trickles down to me.''
</P>
<P>
   TNT (on at 1 p.m. EDT Friday, 10:30 a.m. EDT Saturday and
Sunday) will get Woods' group live in the second round. CBS takes
over at 1:30 p.m. EDT during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''Three or four years ago, you tended to do a broader-based
coverage of a tournament. More golfers got on television,'' said
Turner Sports Senior Vice President Mike Pearl.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, obviously no matter what the story lines are, whether
Tiger is playing well or not playing well, you're focusing a good
bit of coverage on Tiger because the ratings have indicated that
people like to watch Tiger play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratings do tend to be 50-100 percent higher when Woods plays,
but could viewers eventually burn out?
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to get it. The players are already tired of it,''
CBS analyst Gary McCord said. ''But you can't talk about somebody
else when he's pulverizing the field.''
</P>
<P>
   David Feherty, also with CBS, says Woods creates a whole other
set of problems for announcers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew what was possible for me as a player, and part of my
job is to be there on the ground and predict what is possible for
the players. And in that sense, he's redefined my job. I'm not
qualified,'' Feherty said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost as though he skipped a genetic generation, if you
like. There's such a difference between what he can do and what the
next guy can do.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   BUD'S BEST: The scoreboard wasn't ready for Nadia Comaneci at
the 1976 Montreal Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw the scoreboard turning around, and it was 1.00,''
Comaneci recalls, ''and I was like, 'Whoa, that's not so good.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Romanian, of course, had earned a 10 for her routine on the
uneven bars -- the first perfect score in gymnastics history. As the
public address announcer pointed out to the crowd, the scoreboard
had not been programmed to flash numbers higher than 9.95.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of several tidbits in ''Bud Greenspan's Favorite
Stories of Olympic Glory,'' a collection of five documentaries,
airing Sunday at 10 p.m. on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   The program opens with riveting pieces about Comaneci;
Australian swimmer Duncan Armstrong and his excitable coach, Laurie
Lawrence; and Ethiopian marathoner Abebe Bikila. All three are
moving, informative and well-shot. The last two pieces, about
Russian wrestler Alexander Karelin and decathlete Dan O'Brien, are
not as dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, who has won Emmy and Peabody Awards for his sports
chronicles, wrote, directed and produced; Will Lyman narrates.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TRIALS AND ERRORS: Viewers get two chances this weekend to
preview NBC's all-tape coverage of the Sydney Games -- taped
coverage of the U.S. Olympic swimming trials at Indianapolis and
the gymnastics trials at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The gymnastics will be shown on tape Saturday from 8-10 p.m.
EDT/PDT and Sunday from 12-2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   There will be, however, two hours of live coverage Sunday,
starting at 7 p.m. EDT, and including the announcement of the
six-member team by Bela Karolyi's selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   Action from the second half of the swimming trials will be
packaged into a two-hour show airing Saturday at 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   The new bodysuits are ''definitely the biggest buzz on the deck
here,'' analyst Rowdy Gaines said. ''I think it's a great
innovation for our sport. It gives swimming a lot of publicity --
any kind of publicity would be good.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LEAVING EARLY: Fox Sports switched to the Reds-Cubs game
Saturday after the Braves finished beating the Dodgers. Good call.
</P>
<P>
   But then, at 4:27 p.m. EDT, with the Reds leading the Cubs 3-0,
runners at second and third, two outs, and Mark Grace batting ...
Fox went to the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ''And that is, due to contractual obligations, where we must
leave you,'' anchor Keith Olbermann said. ''I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Within about a minute, Grace flew out to left off Danny Graves
to end the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
