<HEADLINE> New-Generation Concorde Discussed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The grounding of the Concorde following a fatal
crash does not spell the end for supersonic passenger jets,
France's transport minister said Thursday, suggesting that a
second-generation aircraft could take its place.
</P>
<P>
   Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot said that a new
generation supersonic aircraft could be a European or even a world
venture that would include the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gayssot spoke on Europe-1 radio a day after France and Britain
withdrew the Concorde's airworthiness certification, meaning that
it is now illegal for the aircraft to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Withdrawing certification is not irreversible, the minister
said. However, modifications must be made before the jet -- which
flies twice the speed of sound -- can take off again.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not the death of the Concorde,'' Gayssot said. ''This
is not the death of supersonic flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspension of the airworthiness certification was recommended by
investigators studying the July 25 crash just after takeoff of a
New York-bound Concorde that killed 113 people.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say high-velocity debris from a tire that ruptured on
takeoff punctured a fuel tank, leading to a catastrophic fire and
engine failure.
</P>
<P>
   French and British aviation officials met Thursday in London to
discuss possible modifications. ''Both sides share the same
determination to work together to find a solution to put Concorde
safely back into service,'' said a brief statement after the
five-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde was developed in the 1960s by France's Sud-Aviation
and British Aircraft Corp. Before the crash, the Concorde had
avoided disaster for 31 years. No other commercial aircraft comes
close to its speed; the sleek jet zipped between Europe and New
York in under four hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
