<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorized scooters law expected to reach Assembly by fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Last summer, Brigantine Police Chief
William Ferris took a stand against motorized scooters. He had a
stack of complaints against the new slow-speed vehicles, but he
didn't know exactly how they were supposed to be regulated.
</P>
<P>
   He appealed to the state Division of Motor Vehicles for guidance
after one juvenile who was riding a scooter in the street ignored a
stop sign, causing a car to break hard in order to avoid hitting
him.
</P>
<P>
   The DMV considers scooters motorized vehicles subject to the
same traffic laws as mo-peds.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with that opinion, the chief used a local newspaper to
warn teens that careless driving will not be tolerated. Ferris only
had to confiscate one scooter before the situation got under
control.
</P>
<P>
   ''After that article appeared, the scooters all but disappeared
from the streets ... with exception of a few,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem persists in other communities, including
Barnegat, Belmar, Ramsey and Stafford, said the lawmaker who
drafted a bill that would prohibit scooters on public streets and
sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have unlicensed drivers operating unregistered and
uninsured vehicles. It's a real problem,'' said Assemblyman Kenneth
LeFevre, R-Atlantic. The bill would require scooters to be insured
and registered with the municipality where the owner lives.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Barnegat police, fed up with people riding scooters
on sidewalks and jumping curves as if they were on skateboards,
announced they would issue summonses to operators of unregistered
scooters they find on public property - and possibly confiscate
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's ironic is that kids are wearing all kinds of protective
gear with skateboards, but they're not using any protective gear
with the scooters and they go much faster,'' LeFevre said. His bill
would require operators to wear a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   LeFevre expects the bill to reach the full Assembly for a vote
this fall. He had hoped it would become law sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's only a matter of time before something happens,'' he
lamented, noting that teen-age operators are flying through
intersections of busy streets.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, a town could designate a public area for their
use.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular models, the Go-Ped, is made by
California-based Patmont Motor Werks and retails for about $439. It
weighs about 20 pounds, is foldable, and gets about 20 miles on a
quart of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Sullivan, a DMV spokesman, said his department is
''skeptical'' that motorized scooters can be operated safely.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think they are less safe than a bicycle. The wheels are so
small, and they rely so much on the person's balance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the legislation goes forward, and municipalities can
designate a confined area for these vehicles to be used, he said,
''then we'll try to help everyone involved.''
</P>
<P>
   John Tiene, executive director of the Insurance Council of New
Jersey, said scooters could be covered under a typical homeowner's
policy, but the insurance industry would probably have to create a
new insurance product for their use in the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   ''The legislation creates its own special class (for
scooters),'' he said. ''This has to be researched.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
