<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jack Nicklaus' Heart is Heavy  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- The story was sad enough to make the rest
of us cry. It only made Jack Nicklaus more determined to play golf.
</P>
<P>
   A man doesn't win 18 majors without motivation, but for perhaps
the first time in the career of the game's greatest player, you had
to wonder what Nicklaus was using for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   He was on the fourth hole of a practice round Wednesday when the
news he'd been dreading for a long time caught up with him: Helen
Nicklaus, the mother he would remember a day later as ''a tough old
girl,'' was dead, five days short of her 91st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The family resemblance was never sharper than Thursday, when
Nicklaus hovered over a final putt on the 18th green. His heart was
heavy, his shirt was soaked with sweat, and his face was reddened
more by embarrassment than the sun shining mercilessly down
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   He was a foot from carding a 77 and he gathered himself up yet
one more time, heaved a small sigh and tapped the ball into the
hole -- tough and professional to the bitter end.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no desire to be here, I promise you,'' he said
afterward. ''But I felt like this is what she wanted me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   No one but Nicklaus would have dared bring them up, but there
were a few compelling reasons for him to soldier on at Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   This was to be his last PGA Championship, over a course he
designed, paired for the first time ever in a competitive round
with the kid who has removed any lingering doubts about Nicklaus
ever finding a worthy successor. Teaching Tiger Woods a lesson was
not on that list, but it may turn out to be the best reason of them
all.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could tell that his mind really wasn't there initially,''
said Woods, who went on to shoot a 66 for a share of the
first-round lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''But once he got into the rhythm of playing, you can tell his
mind started getting more and more sharp and he started
concentrating more and more on every shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf had never seen anyone like Nicklaus when he burst onto the
scene four decades ago, but Woods' ascension over the last 15
months has dimmed even that memory. But the only way the kid makes
the eclipse total is to be as good as Nicklaus was for as long as
Nicklaus was. And if he looked deep enough into the old man's eyes
Thursday, he got a glimpse of just how daunting that is going to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus was married when he came out on tour during the 1961
season and Jack II, the oldest of his five kids, was born that
September. That means that he won when there was a growing family
at home making demands on his time and tugging at his heartstrings.
It means that he won despite flying back and forth from tournaments
to watch his kids' games, that he kept winning after burying the
most important influence in his life, his father, Charley, in 1970,
and won some more while trying to grow the Golden Bear brand into a
golf course design and equipment empire.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to put it is that Nicklaus has major championship
trophies older than Woods, and the 24 years before he bookended the
first with the last was the same number of years that the kid who
would be king has been alive.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Woods has only as many distractions as he wants, but
invariably the total will climb. He almost lost his father, Earl,
after a heart attack four years ago and when he recalled the night
he spent sleeping in a chair at his father's bedside in the
hospital, the confidence in his voice dropped an octave.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told him, 'You know I want to be here with you.' He says,
'No, get your butt out there so I can watch you on TV. At least
I've got something to look forward to, because I've got tubes and
all this other stuff stuck in me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Woods went out the next morning in the second round of the Tour
Championship with no sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I shot like 9 over par on the front,'' he recalled.
The final tally was a 78. ''It was just a tough, tough round to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   There are going to be tough rounds in the future, the more the
longer Woods pursues Nicklaus down a path where precious few ever
tread. Few of those will be tougher than where Nicklaus walked
Thursday, mourning the woman whose stability provided the base from
which he climbed to the pinnacle of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   He honored that memory by playing yet again with every ounce of
concentration he could muster, with his second son, Steve, 37,
toting his bag. He marveled at Woods, employing weapons he never
had, playing a game even he is unfamiliar with, and tried at age 60
never to fall behind.
</P>
<P>
   What Nicklaus remembered at the end of that day was what scared
his mother most over the last year of her life -- that she would
pass away during one of golf's majors. Turns out she didn't have to
be afraid. Because of all the things Helen Nicklaus willed her son,
the last one turned out to be the strength to be Jack Nicklaus on
one of the toughest days of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
