<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Downhill Course Ready, Fast  </HEADLINE>
By VANIA GRANDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   SNOWBASIN, Utah (AP) -- The 2002 downhill courses, possibly the
most technical in Olympic history, are ready for snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   From a 14,000-seat stadium, spectators will have a majestic view
of competitors slipping down a final chute, flying off a jump and
barreling through the finish line at up to 85 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be action from top to bottom,'' said Herwig
Demschar, Olympic director of alpine sports and former head coach
of the U.S. Women's Ski Team. ''They're going to be rocking.''
</P>
<P>
   The revamped hill will see its first test run Feb. 9-11 in a
Super Series downhill and super-G for the United State's top male
skiers and possibly some of Europe's Olympic contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were coaching (the Europeans), I would take three or four
of my key athletes and let them race,'' Demschar said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Memorizing every turn, jump and fall-away slope is crucial in
downhill, where racers reach blistering speeds and can be thrown
off balance by the slightest error.
</P>
<P>
   The men's World Cup tour will stop in Snowbasin on Feb. 24-25
for downhill and super-G races. Women will be racing at the resort,
10 miles east of Ogden, on March 16-18 in a Super Series downhill
and super-G.
</P>
<P>
   Demschar compared the final wall of Snowbasin's race hill to
that of Kitzbuhel, Austria -- a hair-raising World Cup downhill
considered the Super Bowl of skiing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a highly technical course,'' Demschar said of Snowbasin.
</P>
<P>
   Several sections at the top and bottom dip at a 75-degree angle.
Unlike Kitzbuhel, there is no flat, gliding section.
</P>
<P>
   The course is shorter than many others, Demschar said. Gliding
in a tuck position allows racers to rest some of their muscles. But
at Snowbasin, racers will stay on their ski edges.
</P>
<P>
   The women's course starts 180 yards below the men's, but both
are expected to take about 1 minute, 40 seconds to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers expect 25,000 spectators to show up for each of the
downhill races. Just as many are expected for the men's and women's
super-G and combined event, also at Snowbasin.
</P>
<P>
   Besides 14,000 seats in the U-shaped stadium, there will be
standing room for another 9,000-11,000 visitors. Organizers haven't
decided yet if they'll let spectators hike up or ski down to other
sections of the course.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-by-28-foot video screen at the finish line will show the
race from top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the events, 70 miles of snowmaking pipes were
installed along with 540 computer guided snow guns and several
weather stations. Two timing devices also have been connected.
</P>
<P>
   A poor snow year forced Snowbasin to cancel several professional
races last year, but long range forecasts call for more snow and
cold this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've filled the trenches and ditches so even if it is a low
snow year it will be safe to run the races,'' Demschar said.
</P>
<P>
   Still in the works is a new day lodge, a ski service building,
200 to 300 parking lots, a dozen bus drop off loops, a food and
beverage area and a shorter access road saving 20 minutes of
driving time.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a tremendous new ski area coming out of the ground
here,'' said Jerry Anderson, managing director of venue development
for the Salt Lake Organizing Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
