<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Task Force Gets Tough On Racing  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Harness trainers, drivers and owners
support the New Jersey Racing Commission's decision to get tough on
the industry, a trade group spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission this week created a special task force to police
harness racing against drugged-up horses and unscrupulous workers --
a plan applauded by the industry, said Pat Salerno, executive
administrator of the Standardbred Breeders and Owners Association
of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only way to get to the bottom is to get them to
investigate,'' Salerno said. ''I'd say 99 percent of the industry
is 100 percent honest, but there's always a small majority that's
questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Freehold-based trade group represents 2,500 horse trainers,
owners, breeders and drivers in the harness racing industry.
Harness racing is big business in New Jersey, with the Meadowlands
Race Track alone awarding more than $50 million in annual purses.
</P>
<P>
   But it's an industry that has also had its troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, a judge sentenced driver Richard Wojcio to five
years' probation, $7,500 in fines and 500 hours of community
service for conspiring to fix races at Freehold Raceway. He was
cleared of charges of fixing races.
</P>
<P>
   Wojcio won 405 races and more than $2.4 million in purse money
in 1995, the year before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Racing Commission Deputy Director Michael Vukcevich said the new
task force was created to prevent problems from worsening.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is purely a precautionary measure to make sure the
commission stays one step ahead of individuals who don't follow the
rules,'' Vukcevich said.
</P>
<P>
   One area that concerns the commission is the practice of some in
harness racing continuing to work in the field after they have lost
their licenses to suspension
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to create an awareness in the industry that such
action won't be tolerated. Not only do we want to punish
individuals but we want to create a deterrent effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vukcevich said the committee will also look into remarkable
changes in individual horses' performances, ''to confirm that there
is no illicit activity afoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel will also determine whether the commission's
laboratory is properly screening blood and urine samples from
horses. Under state law, the horses are not allowed to have any
foreign substances in their systems on race day.
</P>
<P>
   Industry regulators must quickly respond to the newest illegal
substances given to race horses to enhance their performance,
Vukcevich said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, about seven horses were stripped of their winnings
when a post-race test was positive, the state official said. That
was out of more than 800 tests given, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main point here is that the vast majority of people in
racing are fair and honest and what we have to do is make sure that
the playing field remains level,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
