<HEADLINE> Baseball Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Royals-Twins:
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Closer Ricky Bottalico is day to day after injuring
a rib on his left side in the ninth inning Thursday. Bottalico
threw nine pitches in the ninth before coming out. ... Johnny
Damon, the first Royals player to score 100 runs in three straight
seasons, is on pace to score 136 times. That would eclipse Kansas
City's single-season record of 133, by Willie Wilson in 1980. ...
Damon's 3-for-5 performance Thursday extended his hitting streak to
12 games. ... Kansas City has 13 home runs in its last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: SS Cristian Guzman needs three triples to tie the AL
record of 21 by a switch hitter. Willie Wilson set the mark in 141
games in 1985. ... Pitching coach Dick Such is spending extra time
with ace Brad Radke, gone 1-2 with an 11.68 ERA in his last three
starts. Overall, the right-hander who signed a $36 million,
four-year contract extension this summer, is just 8-13 with a 4.72
ERA. ... LHP Mark Redman, the AL leader among rookies in victories,
strikeouts and ERA, said he's going to quit thinking about the AL
Rookie of the Year award because it's affecting him. He took the
loss Thursday, allowing four runs, seven hits and three walks in 4
1-3 innings.
White Sox-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Despite splitting the four-game series in Baltimore,
the White Sox have the best road record in baseball (39-26). ...
Magglio Ordonez went 0-for-4, ending an eight-game hitting streak,
but is 14-for-26 on the road trip. ... Tony Graffanino has hit
safely in 15 of his 19 starts. ... LF Carlos Lee had the only two
putouts that White Sox outfielders recorded. First baseman Paul
Konerko had 15 of the team's 24 putouts.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: The two runs Ryan Kohlmeier allowed in the ninth were
the first he'd given up since coming to the majors earlier this
month; he had thrown 9 2-3 scoreless innings before Thursday. ...
John Parrish threw 63 strikes and 61 balls in his 6 2-3 innings.
... Jeff Conine started in different positions in each of the four
games of the series: LF, DH, 1B and RF. ... SS Melvin Mora made
errors in all four games of the series.
Angels-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Anaheim began the day 20-19 against the AL East, after
going 20-36 last year. ... Angels have homered in 26 of 32 games
since the All-Star break, with a total of 45. ... Kent Mercker made
his second start since a cerebral hemorrhage on May 11. He went 3
2-3 innings Saturday, also against Denny Neagle and the Yankees.
... Darin Erstad hit his 20th homer Wednesday night at Toronto,
becoming the sixth player in franchise history to have 20 homers
and 20 stolen bases. Devon White (1987) was the previous to
accomplish the feat. Don Baylor (1977-79) and Bobby Bonds (30-30 in
1977) are the others. ... Ron Gant is hitting .269 (7-for-26) with
four home runs and six RBIs since joining the Angels. Four of his
last five hits have been homers, including three solo shots. ...
Troy Glaus hit his 35th homer Wednesday, most since Reggie Jackson
hit a club-record 39 in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Yankees began the night with 27-15 record since July
1, second in the majors to San Francisco (29-13). New York improved
from a three-game deficit in the AL East to a four-game lead during
the stretch. ... C Jorge Posada turned 29 Thursday. ... LHP Denny
Neagle began the night with three straight losses after winning his
previous five decisions -- three with Cincinnati. ... Jose Canseco
began the night having reached base in 14 of 27 plate appearances,
including seven walks, since joining the Yankees. ... OF David
Justice began the game batting .350 (49-for-140) with 10 HRs, 31
RBIs and 25 runs scored in 39 games with the Yankees.
Rangers-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers have lost their last six series against teams
from the AL East since sweeping Baltimore from May 18-21. On
Thursday, they opened a four-game series at Boston, second in the
AL East, before playing three games at the New York Yankees, the AL
East leader, on their two-city road trip. ... It didn't take Gabe
Kapler long to start hitting again. On Wednesday night, his 28-game
hitting streak, longest in the majors, ended when he went 0-for-4
against the Yankees. On Thursday night, he beat out a grounder into
the shortstop hole for a single in his first at-bat. ... Texas
entered the game with a dubious distinction. It had grounded into
117 double plays, most in the majors. Make that 118. Ricky Ledee
hit into one after Kapler's second-inning single off Tim Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: It's official. The Red Sox said Pedro Martinez was their
probable starter for Saturday's game. He left Monday night's game
against Tampa Bay after four innings with a stiff right shoulder.
On Wednesday, he threw for 10 minutes and said he felt fine. The
major league ERA leader will face Texas' Matt Perisho. ... Nomar
Garciaparra is struggling through a 1-for-10 slump that has dropped
his AL-best batting average to .377 and dealt a severe blow to his
hopes of hitting .400, so Boston manager Jimy Williams kept him out
of the starting lineup. Texas starter Rick Helling had to be
pleased since Garciaparra was 12-for-26 in his career against him.
... 2B Mike Lansing got his first game off since he began playing
for the Red Sox after they obtained him from Colorado on July 27.
He was in uniform the next day but didn't play, then was in 17
straight games, batting .231. Jose Offerman started in his place.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Rockies-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Todd Helton finished the road trip hitting .655
(19-for-29) with nine doubles, three homers and seven walks. ...
Rockies are 19-11 against left-handed starters (only Arizona with
20 has more wins against lefty starters in the NL). ... Masato
Yoshii has lost six of his last seven starts since winning three in
a row in July. ... Todd Hollandsworth had two of the Rockies four
hits against the four Mets pitchers Thursday and is 7-for-32 (.219)
since being acquired by the Rockies July 31 from the Los Angeles
Dodgers. ... Former Met Butch Huskey was 1-for-8 in the four-game
series that marked his return to Shea Stadium, where he played 4l4
games for the Mets (1993-98) before moving to Boston and Minnesota
in the AL. ... Reliever Bobby Chouinard allowed home runs in both
his appearances in the series, one to Todd Zeile Tuesday night and
one to Robin Ventura on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The Mets have won seven of their last nine home games,
15 of the last 18 and have 43 home wins, the most in the majors.
... The Mets have won seven consecutive series since losing
two-of-three to Atlanta from July 21-23. ... Turk Wendell's six
strikeouts in relief of Mike Hampton was a career best (he struck
out five twice, most recently in 1995 for the Chicago Cubs). ...
Benny Agbayani's home run in the fifth inning was his 10th of the
season, giving the Mets seven hitters with 10 or more homers,
matching the club-record accomplished in 1986, 1987 and 1990. ...
Todd Zeile and Agbayani homered back-to-back in the fifth inning,
the 11th time this season the Mets have had successive batters
homer. ... Robin Ventura had sacrifice flies in his first two
at-bats, matching a Mets record (done several times, including last
season by Rey Ordonez). ... Ventura has 18 RBIs in his last 16
games. ... Mike Bordick has hit safely in 14 of the 19 games he has
played with the Mets and is batting .311 (23-for-74) since being
acquired July 28 from Baltimore.
Giants-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Shawn Estes won his seventh straight decision to
raise his record to 12-3. ... RF Marvin Benard bunted for singles
in each of his first two at-bats. He tried again in the fifth and
was thrown out. ... Barry Bonds, who homered for the second
straight game, has 28 homers at Olympic Stadium, the most by an
opposing player and two more than Mike Schmidt. Including six
homers at Jarry Park, Schmidt hit a record 32 at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos, who completed an 0-7 homestand, have lost
12 of their last 13 home games. ... LF Peter Bergeron left
following the fourth with a bruised left thumb and was taken to a
hospital for X-rays, which were negative. ... Lenny Webster, who
was taken out of the starting lineup just prior to the game, has a
strained right elbow. X-rays were negative. ... The Expos' worst
homestand was an 0-8 performance against Los Angeles, San Diego and
San Francisco from May 27-June 4, 1969.
</P>
