<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neo-Nazis Remember Hitler Deputy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Right-wing extremists marked the anniversary of
the death of Hitler deputy Rudolf Hess by unfurling banners
Thursday, a day after the government approved $35 million to fight
racism.
</P>
<P>
   The banners and posters declaring ''Rudolf Hess, Martyr for
Peace,'' and similar slogans, were hung from bridges and buildings
in the eastern German communities of Dresden, Gotha and Rudolstadt,
as well as over a highway in western Hesse state, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, about 60 neo-Nazis marched through the city of
Rostock on the Baltic coast with burning torches, shouting ''Rudolf
Hess, our leader,'' according to police.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they detained several people over incidents related
to the Hess anniversary. The officials did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   A Berlin court on Wednesday upheld city officials' decision to
deny a parade permit for Saturday to a neo-Nazi who wanted to mark
Hess' death. A court said that such a march would be ''unbearable''
for the general public in light of recent violence against
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a wave of neo-Nazi violence, the German Cabinet on
Wednesday approved $35 million in spending over three years to
support youth programs fighting racism, anti-Semitism and hatred of
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The government also will establish a nationwide hotline people
can use to alert police to ''drunken skinheads'' on the streets,
and has set up a $4.7 million fund to help victims of neo-Nazi
violence, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Family Ministry said the money would support projects that
try to integrate young people into careers and society and to
combat right-wing extremism.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians, trade union and church leaders and other public
figures have led calls to prevent the kind of right-wing violence
against foreigners and the homeless that has left at least two
people dead this year.
</P>
<P>
   According to government statistics, 129 xenophobic offenses were
registered in June, 29 more than in the same month last year. That
included 28 violent right-wing attacks which left one person dead
and 26 injured.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary of Hess's death has become a rallying point for
right-wing extremists. He committed suicide in Berlin's Spandau
prison on Aug. 17, 1987. His family claims the 93-year-old Hess was
murdered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 2028 </TRAILER>
