<DOCNO> APW20000817.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Opposition Leader Makes Claims  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Alejandro Toledo, repeating claims he was
denied Peru's presidency in a rigged election, is accusing
government forces of raiding his offices around the country and
hauling away computers full of political data.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, who said he is preparing a ''parallel government with a
shadow cabinet'' in the capital Lima, said he talked informally
with President Clinton on Monday, the day the raids occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were robbed. I don't have the empirical evidence, but I
know without a doubt it was the intelligence services of the
Fujimori government,'' Toledo said in an interview Wednesday at the
Democratic National Convention. He has been attending the
convention with other foreign dignitaries as an observer.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said his party has backup data from the computers, but
simultaneous pre-dawn raids were staged on five offices around the
country and their computers stolen. A security guard was injured at
the Lima offices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the allegations Thursday, a congresswoman from
Fujimori's Peru 2000 party said the National Intelligence Service
has better things to do than ransack Toledo's offices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Toledo is constantly making all sorts of allegations
against the Peruvian government, against the image of the Peruvian
government, against the image of Peru,'' Carmen Lozada said.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said the meeting with Clinton had not been scheduled, but
the president approached him at a Los Angeles luncheon where
Clinton spoke to foreign observers of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   According to Toledo, Clinton told him he has been closely
following his candidacy and the fight for democracy in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said thank you for participating in democracy and for
leading the democratic forces in Peru,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Security Council, David Stockwell,
said that while he could not specifically confirm the conversation,
it could have taken place during the luncheon and the description
acurately describes the president's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who Toledo said joined
the conversation, left Peru off her current Latin American trip.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who was in Argentina on Thursday, expressed concern at
the start of her trip about methods Fujimori used to win
re-election to a third consecutive term in a runoff vote that was
criticized by international monitors as flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, who is credited with taming Peru's leftist rebels and
improving the economy, denies fraud in the election.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he fully supports Organization of American States
(OAS) proposals for strengthening democracy in Peru, including
reforms in the judicial system, increased civilian control of the
military, and protection of human rights and freedom of expression
and the press.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen computers held names of opposition leaders and
information on the party structure, Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The strategy is very similar of what Hitler used,'' he said.
''They want to hit me. They can't hit me directly, so they go to
people who are around me.'' He said the security forces took
advantage of his being out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo claims he won 51 percent of the presidential vote in a
May 29 runoff in May and should have been declared victor. He
boycotted a second runoff.
</P>
<P>
   In Lima, meanwhile, a poll by the independent Apoyo research
organization, found that Toledo's popularity may be fading. It
found his approval rating for Toledo at 26 percent, compared with
45 percent for Fujimori. The poll claims a margin of error of plus
or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, who faces several charges in connection with violent
anti-government protests, said he would return to Lima after the
Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not leaving the country,'' he said. ''I'm not going to let
him have it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo accused Fujimori security forces of provoking the
violence in demonstrations against his July 28 inauguration.
Several government buildings were set ablaze, and six people died
in one fire at a government bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of American States has set up face-to-face
meetings between Fujimori government officials and the opposition
for next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
