<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The San Francisco 49ers' problems don't stop.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Steve Mariucci suggested center Chris Dalman's neck injury
might be worse than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Dalman, a starter for the last four years, was hurt early last
week during a blocking drill at the team's training camp at the
University of the Pacific. He was caught among defensive tackle
Brenston Buckner, tackle Scott Gragg and another player when he
went down.
</P>
<P>
   An MRI exam showed disc damage, but it was hoped Dalman would
respond to treatment with anti-inflammatory drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci, however, indicated as the 49ers prepared to break camp
that Dalman's future was uncertain. Dalman was getting additional
medical opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's going to do the smart thing before he even thinks about
getting on the field,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dalman's second neck injury. As a sophomore at Stanford,
he had fusion surgery on the third and fourth vertebrae
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said the team was approaching the situation cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're talking about the neck,'' he said. ''You're talking
about vertebrae''
Patriots:
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Chad Cascadden decided to retire after being plagued
by knee problems that cut short his 1999 season with the New York
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Cascadden, 28, signed with the Patriots on June 26 after being
released by the Jets on March 2 following his fifth NFL season. He
played sparingly in the Patriots' exhibition games, but did take
part in last Friday's 30-20 loss at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've talked to him a couple of times here since the Washington
game and he's not going to continue to play football this year or
anymore,'' said Patriots coach Bill Belichick, his defensive
coordinator in New York.
Rams:
</P>
<P>
   Running back Derek Loville, acquired from Denver on April 5 for
a sixth-round draft pick, was cut Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Loville was bothered early in camp by a hamstring injury. In two
exhibition games, he carried seven times for 18 yards and caught
two passes for 9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got some young guys that are coming on pretty good right
now, and it looks like Derek might be toward the end,'' coach Mike
Martz said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, first-round draft pick Trung Canidate's injured ankle
has improved to the point where he might play in next week's
preseason finale at Dallas. Originally, there was concern that
Canidate might not be ready until late September, missing three or
four regular-season games.
Giants:
</P>
<P>
   Running back Sean Bennett, an important part of New York's
multi-formation offense, has been told to have surgery on his right
knee that could end his season.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett intends to get a second opinion before making a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm unhappy. I want to play,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The medial collateral ligament in the knee was injured on the
first play of the Giants' preseason opener against Chicago. Bennett
practiced at times the last two weeks, but the Giants had an MRI
exam performed this week.
Colts:
</P>
<P>
   Rookie cornerback Rodregis Brooks was placed on injured reserve
Thursday because of a bulging disc in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, a seventh-round pick from Alabama-Birmingham, missed two
days of practice last week with neck spasms. He practiced early
this week, but again missed the past two days when the spasms
returned.
Dolphins:
</P>
<P>
   Miami signed quarterback Gus Ornstein on Thursday, one day after
waiving Jim Druckenmiller.
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein spent part of training camp with Indianapolis before
being released Aug. 7. He went to camp with St. Louis as an
undrafted rookie free agent in 1999, but also was waived.
</P>
<P>
   He faces the same fate with the Dolphins. Ornstein will be
released next week when Jay Fiedler returns from arthroscopic hip
surgery, coach Dave Wannstedt said. Ornstein was needed to share
practice repetitions with Damon Huard and Mike Quinn.
Broncos:
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Kavika Pittman was fined $6,000 for a hit on Green
Bay quarterback Matt Hasselbeck in Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   On the play, as defensive tackle Trevor Pryce attempted to wrap
up Hasselbeck, Pittman lunged into the quarterback, a hit so strong
it knocked Hasselbeck's helmet off.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I held up as much as I could in the situation,''
Pittman said. ''He was being tackled into my direction, and I was
already airborne with no direct-hit contact and no forearm to the
head. I hit him with my shoulder. So I don't feel like I should get
fined.''
</P>
</TEXT>
