<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golfers Wait at PGA Championships  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS DUNCAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- One hole into the PGA Championship, Ernie
Els had an idea of what to expect out of the round -- and it had
nothing to do with his score.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived on the tee of the par-5 2nd, three groups were
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   About six hours later, he finally walked off the course with a
2-over-par 74.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's ridiculous,'' Els said. ''It takes one group early on to
have a bad hole and the whole field backs up.''
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended by darkness at 8:27 p.m. Thursday with six
groups still on the course. The 18 players were spread out on Nos.
15, 16 and 18. They will complete their first rounds at 9:15 a.m.
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The second round will begin from the first tee, as scheduled, at
7:25 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   PGA senior director of tournaments Kerry Haigh said ''a high
percentage of groups'' were timed by officials after their rounds
had started, but none were assessed the two-stroke penalty that
follows two warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're disappointed in this pace of play,'' Haigh said. ''We
have a pace of play policy, that is certainly enforced and will be
again tomorrow. We expect things to run on schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Haigh said the PGA set a 4-hour, 41-minute limit for every group
to finish its round. Few made that deadline on Thursday. The
threesome of Tiger Woods, Jack Nicklaus and Vijay Singh played its
first round in 4:58, Haigh said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, who played with Els, blamed the delay on the four
par-5s at Valhalla, which are all reachable in two shots by most of
the players in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing can be done,'' said Watson, who shot a 76. ''Play was
delayed on the second tee, the 10th tee and the 18th tee. The
problem is the rough around these par-5s is so bad and the greens
are so tight, if you're struggling, it takes a long time for you to
play those holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Haigh also blamed the par-5s but said there were other factors
causing the delays.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every year at the PGA Championship, we are very limited with
the amount of daylight,'' Haigh said. ''Plus, the heat index is
taxing on everyone, the course is very difficult and it's major
championship conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those factors combine for a trying day.''
</P>
<P>
   Els suggested the PGA should think twice about coming back to
Valhalla, where the PGA was also played four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not criticizing the PGA, but they might have to rethink
playing this golf course,'' he said. ''You put 150 players on a
really tough course and try to finish in one day. You're not going
to do that on this track.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he could not remember playing in a major
championship where first-round play had to be suspended because of
slow play.
</P>
<P>
   ''That has to be the longest round I've played in a major
championship,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Els, Watson and Steve Jones were due to tee off at 9:22 a.m. on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's like it was today, we'll maybe play eight holes in the
morning and the rest of the round in the afternoon,'' Els said.
''I'm not looking forward to tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Leonard, playing in the group behind Els and Watson on
Thursday, teed off at 1:43 p.m. and finished as the sun was
setting, just before 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what the solution is,'' Leonard said. ''For
professional golfers to take six hours to play 18 holes, it's
pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess I don't know enough about golf to know how to fix
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Lanny Wadkins summed it up best when he was asked if he
had time for a quick question after his round.
</P>
<P>
   ''Man, I don't have time for anything,'' Wadkins said, looking
at his watch. ''It's 7:15 p.m. We've been out here six hours. It's
ridiculous. On the senior tour, we take four hours in a cart and
sit down and have a beer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 2136 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
