<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-NJ--Flash Floods-Glance  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton declared flood-ravaged Morris and Sussex
counties disaster areas Thursday, making federal relief funds
available to help New Jerseyans repair their broken homes, bridges
and roads.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster declaration sought by Gov. Christie Whitman clears
the way for the Federal Emergency Management Agency to set up
offices in the area to help residents and towns and assess damages.
An office will be set up within the next few days, Whitman
spokeswoman Laura Otterbourg said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who suffered flood damage will be able to apply for
grants for temporary housing, home repairs or unemployment, or
low-interest loans for home repair. Small businesses can receive
low-interest loans of up to $1.5 million. FEMA funds will also be
available to pay for 75 percent of the cost of rebuilding bridges
and roads that washed away, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, who said she was ''relieved'' by the declaration,
announced the state would pay the remaining 25 percent of any FEMA
grants to replace public property and the remainder of some FEMA
grants that cover home repairs, destroyed personal property or
medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman spokesman Peter McDonough has said damage from the
storm, which dumped more than a foot of rain on some parts of the
two counties, will surpass $100 million. Sussex County officials
have estimated destroyed roads, bridges and homes in their county
alone will cost more than $166 million to repair, while Morris
County officials have an initial damage estimate of $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   The rain on Saturday and Monday, including 14 inches of rain
that fell in Sparta on Saturday, damaged thousands of homes, wiped
out dozens of bridges, roads and dams and forced hundreds to flee
the rising waters.
</P>
<P>
   Police continued a search in Hunterdon County Thursday for a
missing kayaker who went out on the swollen Musconetcong River.
Police found Charles Weaver's kayak on Wednesday about a mile
downstream from where he went missing but had not located the
58-year-old Riegelsville, Pa., man, Holland Township police said.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that floodwaters have produced breeding grounds for
mosquitoes and the West Nile virus, Sussex and Morris counties
stepped up its efforts to kill mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Morlock, administrator of health and public safety for
Sussex County, said six people have been treating stagnant water
harboring mosquito larvae with insecticides, particularly at dams
that burst in Sparta, Byram and Stanhope over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He said the mosquitoes breed in standing water, and the larvae
take 10 to 14 days to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ''We bomb them before they build their aircrafts,'' Morlock
said.
</P>
<P>
   County officials were treating water in Sparta with insecticides
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Morris County Mosquito Commission inspectors were out over the
weekend and on Thursday in Jefferson Township checking standing
water for mosquito larvae and treating it with pesticides,
superintendent Marc Slaff said.
</P>
<P>
   The potentially fatal, mosquito-borne virus killed seven people
in New York and sickened dozens last year. Three Staten Island
residents in New York have tested positive for the virus this year.
</P>
<P>
   Five dams under close watch in Sussex County haven't faltered,
State Police spokesman John Hagerty said. Ten bridges and several
roads remained closed in the county.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and business owners seeking assistance should call
1-800-462-9029 beginning Friday, between 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. seven
days a week. The reference number is 1337. Hearing- or
speech-impaired residents should call 1-800-462-7585.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fema.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-17-00 2142 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
