<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frustrated unions threaten to abandon talks  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Talks aimed at settling a 12-day-old strike by
Verizon Communications workers headed for a crucial phase late
Thursday, as union bargainers threatened to walk out unless the
company presented an acceptable offer.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators said they would walk out at midnight unless they
reached an agreement or could report substantial progress in talks,
which began in late June.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the deadline, the company said it had
''fine-tuned'' its contract proposal, but would give no details.
</P>
<P>
   ''They had talked about wanting to see substantial progress, and
I think we are seeing substantial progress,'' said Verizon
spokesman Eric Rabe.
</P>
<P>
   Myles Calvey, negotiator for the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, said he did not know whether the updated
proposal would prompt the unions to talk past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   IBEW, the smaller of two unions staging the walkout, issued the
ultimatum late Wednesday. Negotiators representing the larger
Communications Workers of America seemed split about whether to
join in abandoning the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The IBEW represents 14,700 employees in New England and upstate
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The strike of 87,200 repair and customer service workers, which
began Aug. 6, affects 25 million Verizon consumers from Maine to
Virginia. Regular phone service is not affected, but the strike has
slowed directory assistance calls and requests for new service and
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon was formed by the June merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   CWA, which has two sets of bargainers, said at least one of the
two negotiating teams also planned to leave the talks at midnight.
They represent workers from New England and New York as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very possible'' that the other team, bargaining on behalf
of workers from New Jersey to Virginia, could set the same
ultimatum, said CWA spokesman Jeff Miller. The combined CWA
negotiators represent more than 72,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe of Verizon said Thursday afternoon that the threatened
walkout by union negotiators could give all parties greater
incentive to wrap up the protracted talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes it's helpful to have a deadline,'' he said. ''It
gets people focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe noted that Verizon is one of the nation's few big
telecommunications companies with a substantial unionized work
force.
</P>
<P>
   ''Frankly, we're the good guys from the standpoint of union
workers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe said Verizon had about 100,000 pending requests for
repairs, about 20,000 more than a week ago and more than three
times the usual number of requests. Storm damage has added to the
repair load, Rabe said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, police in Baldwin, N.Y., said two striking
Verizon workers were in critical condition after cutting an
electric cable in an apparent attempt to sever a telephone line.
The men were charged with criminal tampering and criminal mischief.
</P>
<P>
   Police released details of a second incident on Long Island, in
which a striking employee was charged with reckless endangerment
for allegedly forcing a Bell Atlantic van off the Long Island
Expressway on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon has taken out full-page ads in several newspapers
explaining the dispute to customers. One ad, in Thursday's New York
Times, said of the strike, ''Nobody's winning. Not our company. Not
our customers. Not the union. Not our employees, the very people we
need to keep us competitive in the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike affects Delaware, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, New
Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island,
Vermont, Virginia, West Virginia and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com
</P>
<P>
   Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
