<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Drifter Charged in Deaths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUNDABERG, Australia (AP) -- A drifter was charged Friday with
murder in the deaths of two travelers who perished in a fire that
ripped through a backpackers' hostel in eastern Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Paul Long, 37, was also charged with arson in the June 23
blaze at the Palace Backpackers Hostel that killed 15 people.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not immediately say why Long was charged in the
deaths of only two of the victims -- 22 year-old Western Australian
twins, Kellie June Slarke and Stacey Louise Slarke.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not given a possible motive. One witness has said he
saw Long standing close to the hostel just before flames engulfed
the building.
</P>
<P>
   Long was staying at the hostel in the small town of Childers,
190 miles north of Queensland state capital Brisbane, the night the
aging timber building was torched.
</P>
<P>
   At his hearing Friday, Long -- a short, slightly built man with a
bushy beard -- sat with his hands shackled to a body belt in the
dock, surrounded by three security guards.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom, Long's lawyer John Fraser said his client was
aware of the charges but did not say how his client would plead.
</P>
<P>
   Long was denied bail at the hearing in Bundaberg. His next
hearing was set for Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Long was arrested five days after the fire and charged at that
time with attempted murder for allegedly wounding a police officer
with a knife during his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The hostel was popular among backpackers seeking seasonal
fruit-picking work.
</P>
<P>
   Six backpackers from Britain, four from Australia, two from the
Netherlands and one each from Ireland, South Korea and Japan were
killed in the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the bodies were so burned they could only be identified
through dental records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 2215 </TRAILER>
