<DOCNO> APW20000817.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tutu Returns To Rest in S. Africa  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Archbishop Desmond Tutu, a
leading activist in the struggle against apartheid, returned home
from a two-year sabbatical in the United States Thursday, saying he
planned to take a well-deserved rest.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's so wonderful to be back -- it's enough to move one to
tears,'' he told reporters after arriving at Cape Town's airport.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, who underwent surgery for prostate cancer in November last
year, said his recovery had been slower than expected and pledged
to maintain a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to come home to sleep. We have a cadre of outstanding
new leaders. We oldies, certainly I, should give them space to show
off their worth,'' he said. ''It is now time I move away from
center stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The 69-year-old Anglican archbishop, who won the Nobel Peace
Prize in 1984 for his role in fighting white rule which ended with
all-race election in 1994, subsequently chaired a commission which
probed apartheid-era abuses and gave amnesty to those who confessed
of their involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu said the government and those who benefitted from apartheid
had a duty to pay reparations to people identified by the
commission as victims of the evil system.
</P>
<P>
   The jovial archbishop is widely revered and loved in South
Africa, with his personable manner endearing him to people across
the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, who was lecturing theology at Emory University in Atlanta,
showed his manner had not changed while he was away from South
Africa. He went down on his knee to tie a photographer's shoelace
and enthusiastically embraced supporters who had arrived to welcome
him home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 2220 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bronx Little League team loses in regional final  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - It's a mantra familiar to baseball teams of all
ages: Wait 'till next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Rolando Paulino All Stars from the Bronx lost 1-0 Thursday
night to the Goffstown, N.H. team in the Eastern Regional Little
League title. The New Hampshire team will go on to the Little
League World Series, which begins Sunday in Williamsport, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Three busloads of parents and fans made the 2&AMP;frac12;-hour drive to
Connecticut to cheer the team of 9-to-12-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the team's main supporters, Bronx Borough President
Fernando Ferrer, missed the game because he was attending the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But the borough president sent a telegram wishing the team luck
and promised to call youngsters after the game, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   ''The spirited and dynamic Rolando Paulino All-Stars are an
inspiration to all the residents of the Bronx,'' Ferrer said.
''They persevered against tough opponents, and in doing so they
have made us all proud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
