<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradstreet portrait tops auction at $40,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. (AP) - A 240-year-old portrait of a prominent
Colonial general fetched $40,000 Thursday night at an auction of
items discovered this year upon the death of an area woman.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the auction, the only known existing portrait
of Gen. John Bradstreet, sold to William Reese, a collector from
New Haven, Conn. In the portrait by Thomas Mc ilworth, Bradstreet,
a veteran of the French and Indian War, sits stiffly without
expression.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Carter, of Acorn Auction and Estates, said the price
was eight times higher than the previous sale topper for a painting
by Mc ilworth, perhaps driven by an increasing understanding of
Bradstreet's prominence in Colonial America.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's come forward as a more important Albany figure
than previously thought,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   She did not have a total tally on the night but said every item
sold and the auction house ''got top dollar for the majority of the
items.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had (bidders) represented from all over the country,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other items recovered earlier this year included letters to
Bradstreet's step-granddaughter, Martha Bradstreet, from Aaron Burr
and Francis Scott Key, yellowed deeds and wills, hand-drawn maps of
old Utica and newspapers reporting Custer's last stand and
President Johnson's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Burr was a vice president and the man who killed Alexander
Hamilton. Key wrote the ''Star Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   And, like her step-grandfather, the auction prices for the
Martha Bradstreet memorabilia show she was a significant player in
19th century New York, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our belief about Martha was vindicated,'' Carter said. ''She
was perceived as a more important character than previously
believed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
