<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Governor Plans Abortion Poll  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The governor of Guanajuato state says he will
let the people decide whether he should approve or veto a highly
controversial proposal to criminalize abortion in the case of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Ramon Martin Huerta said he would contract an outside
polling firm to survey citizens before making his own executive
decision on the bill the state legislature approved earlier this
month, the Reforma newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm putting this before the citizenry and will abide by what
they say,'' said Martin Huerta, who has declined to offer a public
opinion on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Guanajuato legislators from the conservative National Action
Party of President-elect Vicente Fox passed the bill on Aug. 3,
igniting a nationwide debate over the issue and raising fears about
the party's conservative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The move also prompted Mexico City's leftist mayor to submit her
own proposal that would decriminalize abortion when the life of the
mother is threatened or when the fetus has severe birth defects.
That proposal must be approved by the federal district's
legislature, a majority of which reportedly is leaning toward
supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Mexico City law allows abortions in the case of rape.
</P>
<P>
   In most of Mexico's 31 states, abortion is allowed in cases of
rape or when the life of the mother or the baby is in danger. In
other cases, abortion is illegal, punishable by one to five years
in jail for the mother and 10 for the doctor who performs it.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, struggling to bury historical fears of his party's socially
conservative stance, has said he would not support a
Guanajuato-style initiative at the federal level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 2254 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Counties Named Disaster Areas  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- President Clinton declared two flood-ravaged
New Jersey counties disaster areas Thursday, making federal relief
funds available to help residents repair broken homes, bridges and
roads.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster declaration also clears the way for the Federal
Emergency Management Agency to assess the damage and set up offices
in the area to help residents and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain damaged thousands of homes, forced hundreds of people
to flee rising waters and wiped out dozens of bridges, roads and
dams. The city of Sparta in northwest New Jersey received 14 inches
of rain on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
