<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Aug. 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Accepts Democratic Presidential Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Al Gore launched his fall quest for the White House
Thursday, pledging a ''better, fairer, more prosperous America'' in the
climactic speech of the Democratic National Convention. Acknowledging ''my own
imperfections'' he said nonetheless, ''I stand here tonight as my own man,''
after eight years as vice president. In the final minutes of his convention,
Gore entered the hall to a thunderous ovation. ''In the name of all the working
families who are the strength and soul of America,'' he said, ''I accept your
nomination.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lieberman Claims VP Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- On the day he became the first Jewish vice presidential
candidate of a major U.S. political party, Joseph Lieberman spent hours trying
to shore up support among influential Democratic constituencies. Before his
nomination was formally ratified tonight, Lieberman held a flurry of private
meetings with leaders of labor, women's groups and teachers' organizations. His
slogan for the day: ''Winning is the whole deal.'' Later, with a single mighty
shout, delegates to the Democratic National Convention snapped a long-standing
assumed religious barrier by nominating Lieberman.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tutu Returns to South Africa
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Archbishop Desmond Tutu, a leading activist
in the struggle against apartheid, returned home from a two-year sabbatical in
the United States Thursday, saying he planned to take a well-deserved rest.
''It's so wonderful to be back -- it's enough to move one to tears,'' he told
reporters after arriving at Cape Town's airport. Tutu, who underwent surgery for
prostate cancer in November last year, said his recovery had been slower than
expected and pledged to maintain a low profile.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Grand Jury To Hear Lewinsky Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Independent Counsel Robert Ray has empaneled a new grand
jury to hear evidence against President Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky scandal
as he tries to determine if criminal charges are warranted, legal sources said
today, and the news angered Democrats on the night Vice President Al Gore was to
accept the party's presidential nomination at its convention in Los Angeles.
''It's probably just another Republican dirty trick,'' Rep. Charles Rangel,
D-N.Y., said. The move follows through on Ray's promise to consider whether the
president should be indicted after he steps down from office next January. Legal
experts cautioned the decision doesn't mean charges will ever be filed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sunken Russian Sub Has Hole on Side
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The sunken submarine Kursk has a ''terrifying hole'' on its
starboard side, a top Russian official said today as new underwater film
indicated that an explosion wrecked the vessel and sent it plunging to the sea
bottom in seconds. Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov said most of the nuclear
submarine's 118 crewmen were likely in the damaged section of the vessel,
suggesting they had no time to escape.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Telephone Talks 'Deadline' Tonight
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Talks aimed at settling a 12-day-old strike by Verizon
Communications workers headed for a crucial phase late today, as union
bargainers threatened to walk out unless the company presented an acceptable
offer.The negotiators said they would walk out at midnight unless they reached
an agreement or could report substantial progress in talks, which began in late
June. Also today, police in Baldwin, N.Y., said two striking Verizon workers
were in critical condition after cutting an electric cable in an apparent
attempt to sever a telephone line.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Air Force Launches Satellite
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) -- The Air Force successfully launched
a Titan 4B rocket today that carried a classified satellite into orbit. The
rocket was visible across a wide area of California as it rose over the Pacific
Ocean. Titan 4 launches have been closely watched since three consecutive
failures in 1998 and 1999. One blew up and the other two put satellites into
wrong orbits.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Edge Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks edged higher early Friday in summer
holiday-thinned trading. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained
20.90 points, or 0.13 percent, to 16,181.93 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Thursday, the average closed down 195.00 points, or 1.19 percent.In
New York, the Dow rose 47.25 points to 11,055.64 points at Thursday's close. The
Nasdaq closed at 3,940.87, up 79.67.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees Beat Angels 6-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Denny Neagle scattered nine hits in 6 2-3 innings, and
Glenallen Hill, David Justice and Luis Sojo homered tonight to lead the New York
Yankees over the Anaheim Angels 6-1. Neagle (3-3) stopped his three-game losing
streak as he rebounded from his shortest outing in over a year, when he allowed
six earned runs in 1 2-3 innings in the Yankees' 9-6 loss at Anaheim last
Saturday.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
