<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Trying To Connect to Voters  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Famously wooden, Al Gore never claimed he was
Mr. Personality. He tried to connect with voters Thursday night
using a homespun biography and a thick briefcase of ideas about
Social Security, better schools, a patients' bill of rights and
much, much more.
</P>
<P>
   The goal: to persuade Americans he can be just as likable as
George W. Bush -- but has a lot more experience and substance.
Friends and family lined up on the final night of the Democratic
National Convention to humanize Gore's image with stories of his
determination, humor, spontaneity and decision making.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problem, though, is that he's been struggling for well
over a year to introduce -- and reintroduce -- himself to voters. To
define and redefine himself. Eight years the understudy, he has
been overshadowed by President Clinton and denied credit for the
nation's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stand here tonight as my own man and I want you to know me
for who I truly am,'' Gore said. He raced over applause in his
51-minute address to keep on speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that sometimes people say I'm too serious, that I talk
too much substance and policy,'' Gore acknowledged. ''Maybe I've
done that tonight. But the presidency is more than a popularity
contest. It's a day-by-day fight for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bush, Gore had some unwelcome distractions in Los
Angeles. There were arguments over a Playboy mansion fund-raiser
and news of a fresh grand jury investigation of Clinton. Gore
running mate Joseph Lieberman had to spend time mending fences with
blacks and others, underscoring splits within the Democratic ranks.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gore's biggest hurdles, reflected in the polls, is that
at least four of 10 Americans don't like him, won't vote for him
and haven't shown much inclination to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   The Voter.com-Battleground tracking poll this week suggested
Gore may be starting to chip away at those numbers during his
convention. But Bush is liked by twice as many voters as those who
dislike him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Democrats don't hate Bush as much as Republicans hate Gore,''
said Democratic pollster Celinda Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's something off-putting about the guy,'' said Jim Duffy,
a Democratic consultant who worked with Gore in his failed
presidential campaign in 1988. ''He just hasn't been able to
connect with people the same way Clinton does or even Bush is able
to do. He's not a good people politician. He's a much more cerebral
politician.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also has been hurt by voters' weariness over
the long political saga involving Clinton's affair with Monica
Lewinsky -- an episode that came back again on the very day Gore
accepted his party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Legal sources said Independent Counsel Robert Ray had empaneled
a new grand jury to hear evidence against Clinton. The White House
complained that the timing of the leak ''reeks to high heavens.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush managed to project a lot of confidence at his convention.
He could exult that Republicans were united. But there was a lot of
nail biting among Democrats in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden of Delaware said, ''There's a lot of
anxiety hanging over this convention'' because Democrats ''can't
understand how a guy like George W. Bush can be leading a guy with
the kind of caliber, experience and know-how as Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   White House chief of staff John Podesta said Bush was benefiting
from America's desire ''for a dynamic candidate'' who can bring
change.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Gore adviser said the Democratic convention hadn't gone
as planned. The first two days were ''a little ragged'' and that
raised the stakes for Gore's speech Thursday night, the adviser
said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Clinton's convention speech dragged past 11 p.m.
EDT when a huge part of the television audience was lost. There
also was second guessing about Lieberman's remarks about mending
affirmative action, comments that reinforced an emerging story line
alleging political flip-flops. Democrats had to devote Tuesday
night to trying to solidify the party's base of core voters.
</P>
<P>
   Merle Black, professor of politics at Emory University, said
Gore's real challenge is project himself as a likable politician
whom voters want to root for.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bush had that going for him in Philadelphia,'' Black said.
''He came across in his speech as a likable person. He got stronger
as he went through the speech. A lot of Americans could buy into
that because they liked him, hoped it works out that kind of way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Oppenheimer, political scientist at Vanderbilt University,
said Gore should highlight his skills and not worry about
comparisons with Clinton or Bush. ''If you try to do what you can't
do, then you're Mike Dukakis riding in a tank,'' Oppenheimer said.
''So be yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Terence Hunt has covered the Reagan, Bush and
Clinton presidencies for The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 2309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000817.0222 </DOCNO>
