<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-17 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox 8, Rangers 7  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Mike Lansing's second two-run double in two
innings capped a three-run rally in the ninth that gave the Boston
Red Sox an 8-7 win over the Texas Rangers on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing, whose 15 hits for the Red Sox before Thursday were all
singles, didn't start for the first time in 18 games since he was
acquired from Colorado on July 27.
</P>
<P>
   With Boston trailing 6-2, he pinch hit for Brian Daubach in the
eighth and doubled in two runs, then scored as Troy O'Leary's
infield single to first was thrown wildly for an error by Rafael
Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Then Texas made it 7-5 on Rusty Greer's third double of the game
in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox didn't seem to have much of a chance. They had
stranded 13 runners, including men in scoring position in each of
the first seven innings, and John Wetteland, who had 26 saves in 33
opportunities, came in to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But he ran into trouble with two outs when Scott Hatteberg
walked and Jose Offerman singled to right.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gilkey hit a routine grounder to shortstop, but Royce
Clayton had trouble getting the ball out of his glove, and Gilkey
reached on the error, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox already had left the bases loaded in the second and
seventh innings, but they didn't waste this chance.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland (4-5) hit Carl Everett, who had struck out in his
previous three at-bats, cutting the lead to 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing then lined a 1-and-1 pitch off the left-field wall for
Boston's 18th hit, driving in the decisive runs and sending his
teammates racing out of the dugout to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Garces (8-0) allowed one run in one inning on consecutive
doubles by Frank Catalanotto and Greer as Boston remained four
games behind the AL East-leading New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Red Sox had come from behind with a
three-run eighth inning that gave them a 4-3 win over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Greer and Catalanotto drove in three runs each for the Rangers,
who had taken a 3-1 lead on Catalanotto's two-run homer in the
third and Bill Haselman's solo shot in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Texas added three runs in the seventh, one on a wild throw to
second on a potential double-play grounder to Tim Wakefield and two
on Greer's double.
</P>
<P>
   Boston scored in the seventh on O'Leary's 10th homer and added
three in the eighth against Jeff Zimmerman and Mike Venafro.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox scored their first run off Rick Helling on Carl
Everett's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Helling-Wakefield matchup was a replay of last
Saturday's pairing in Texas, won by the Rangers 6-3. ... Lou
Merloni is 9-for-16 in four games since being called up from
Triple-A Pawtucket on Monday. He went 3-for-5 Thursday. ... Gabe
Kapler went 1-for-5 for Texas, one day after his 28-game hitting
streak, longest in the majors this season, ended. ... Helling threw
118 pitches, increasing his AL-high total to 3,047.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 2312 </TRAILER>
