<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Visits Argentina Bomb Site  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE NORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright toured the site of a 1994 bombing attack on a Jewish
community center Thursday, showing solidarity with Washington's
allies in the fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who is on a five-nation tour of South America, joined
Foreign Minister Adalberto Rodriguez Giavarini and Jewish leaders
to pay homage to the 86 victims in a solemn visit to the rebuilt
center.
</P>
<P>
   Albright later traveled to Santiago, Chile, where she promised
that the United States would continue to declassify documents
related to the 1973-1990 dictatorship of Gen. Augusto Pinochet. She
noted that after massive disclosures in June and September 1999,
some 11,000 additional documents are earmarked for declassification
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The documents refer to relations between the United States and
Chile under Pinochet, including information on some cases of human
rights violations here.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference in the Chilean capital, the secretary
also touted a U.S. program to promote peace and battle drugs in
Colombia, saying she has received strong support from other nations
for the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said reports that Brazil was cool to the multi-million
dollar ''Colombia Plan'' were wrong. She stressed she was not
requesting financial backing for the plan in the countries she is
visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with Albright, Chilean Foreign Minister Soledad Alvear
said Chile ''strongly supports the plan'' as a move in defense of
the elected democratic government of Colombian Presiden Andres
Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration plan calls for a U.S. commitment of
$1.3 billion and $621 million from other nations for beleaguered
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, Albright stood on the patio of the fortress-like
building Jewish center, beside a monument emblazoned with the Star
of David and a stone plaque etched with the word ''REMEMBER'' and
the names of the victims of the July 18, 1994, attack.
</P>
<P>
   Although Albright did not comment in public, a senior State
Department official said the secretary wanted to show solidarity
with the victims in her last appearance of a two-day visit to
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is to show solidarity with Argentina for its strong
support of efforts to fight terrorism, both through the
Organization of American States and through other forums,'' said
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Little progress has been made in arresting the masterminds of
either the bombing of the Jewish center or the 1992 bombing of the
Israeli Embassy that killed 22 people. The bombings shook
Argentina's 220,000-member Jewish community, the largest in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the new eight-story Jewish center was inaugurated,
complete with double metal doors and concrete walls. Photographs of
the first center, which was destroyed, hang in a ground-floor
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion has fallen on 15 former police officers in the Jewish
center bombing. Prosecutors say most had accessory roles such as
procuring the car used in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando De la Rua took office in December and pledged
to make the bombing investigations a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have complained that investigators under former
president Carlos Menem weren't thorough.
</P>
<P>
   ''We welcome this meeting,'' said Rogelio Cichowolsky, president
of the Delegation of Jewish Associations, after Albright sat down
with Jewish leaders to discuss the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   They also spoke about an estimated 2,000 Jewish victims missing
under Argentina's 1976-83 military dictatorship and the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very important that Albright came today because the
families of the victims specifically asked for U.S. help in
investigating this case,'' said Sofia Guterman, whose only child,
Andrea, 28, was killed in the Jewish center attack.
</P>
<P>
   She regularly joins relatives of other victims to light candles
and call for justice.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Albright's visit to the site would focus attention on
the case, she said: ''Yes, absolutely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-17-00 2318 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
